{"title_page": "Abdul Majed", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Abdul Majed\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = <!--{{Birth date|df=yes|1950|5|5}}-->\n| birth_place   = Batamara, Borhanudding Upazilla, Bhola\n| death_date    = <!--{{Death date and age|df=yes|2010|10|10|1950|5|5}}-->\n| occupation    = Military Personel\n| years_active  = \n| allegiance    =\n| branch        = \n| criminal_charges   = <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources -->\n| criminal_penalty   =  \n| criminal_status    = \n| burial_place       = \n| mother             = \n| father             = Ali Mia Chowdhury\n| serviceyears  = \n| rank          = Captain\n}}\n\n'''Abdul Majid''' is a former Bangladesh Army officer who was convicted for his role in the 1975 [[Jail Killing Day|Jail Killing]] following the [[Assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]], the founding father of Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bangabandhu's killer Abdul Majed arrested, sent to jail |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/news/bangabandhus-killer-abdul-majed-arrested-police-1890487 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Dailystar |date=7 April 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news |title=Condemned Mujib killer Majed held |url=https://www.newagebd.net/article/103972/mujib-killer-majed-arrested |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=New Age |language=en}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\n\n==Career==\nAbdul Majed, was a sacked army captain of Bangladesh Army.  Majed was appointed to the Bangladesh Embassy in Senegal. He retired from Bangladesh Army in 1980 and joined the civil administration as a Deputy Secretary. He worked at the [[Bangladesh Inland Water Transport Corporation]]. He was promoted to the rank of Secretary. He joined the Ministry of Youth and Sports as the director of youth development. He was appointed the Director of [[National Savings Directorate]]. He disappeared in 1997 after [[Sheikh Hasina]], daughter of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, was voted Prime Minister of Bangladesh.<ref name=\"starlast\"></ref>\n\n==Conviction==\nOn 14 August 1975, he and other officers looted weapons from Bangal Lancers armory. On 15 August 1975, Sheikh Mujibur Rahman and most of his family members were killed in the [[15 August 1975 Bangladesh coup d'\u00e9tat]]. He meet the other officers met at Bangabhaban and created a new government with [[Khandaker Mushtaq Ahmed]] in charge.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mohiuddin's confession |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/august-15-special-coverage/mohiuddins-confession-1269646 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Daily Star |date=19 November 2009 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Shahriar's confession |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/august-15-special-coverage/shahriars-confession-1269637 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Daily Star |date=19 November 2009 |language=en}}</ref> He was part of the team that attacked the residence of [[Abdur Rab Serniabat]], brother-in-law of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman.<ref>{{cite news |title=No justice yet in 3 other Aug 15 cases |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-150810 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Daily Star |date=15 August 2010 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=FACTBOX: Aug 15 victims |url=https://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/bangabandhu-appeals/2009/11/19/factbox-aug-15-victims |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=bdnews24.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 November 1975, he and the other army officers involved in the assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman meet Khandaker Mushtaq Ahmed at the Bangabhaban. There a decision was made to carry out the [[Jail Killing Day|Jail Killing]] to kill four national leaders of Bangladesh Awami League. The leaders were [[Abul Hasnat Muhammad Qamaruzzaman]], [[Muhammad Mansur Ali]], [[Syed Nazrul Islam]], and [[Tajuddin Ahmed]].<ref name=\"starmid\">{{cite news |title=Mushtaq met all accused on Nov 2 night |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-267225 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Daily Star |date=31 January 2013 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn November 19, 2009, [[Supreme Court of Bangladesh|Bangladesh Supreme Court]] upheld the death sentences of Majed and 11 other self-confessed killers of  Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman. Five of them were executed on January 27, 2010.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bangabandhu Mujibur Rahman's killer Abdul Majed arrested in Bangladesh |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/world/2020/apr/07/bangabandhu-mujibur-rahmans-killer-abdul-majed-arrested-in-bangladesh-2126964.html |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=The New Indian Express |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, he was sentenced to death on the assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman case by a trial court.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Press |first1=Associated |title=Killer of Bangladesh independence leader arrested after 45 years on run |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/07/killer-of-bangladesh-independence-leader-arrested-after-45-years-on-run |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 November 2009, Majed death sentence was confirmed by Bangladesh Supreme Court along with 12 other convicts in the case over the [[Assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]]. Five of the convicts were executed on 27 January 2010. They were [[AKM Mohiuddin Ahmed]], [[Bazlul Huda]], [[Mohiuddin Ahmed]], [[Syed Farooq Rahman]], and [[Sultan Shahriar Rashid Khan]]. Another convict, [[Abdul Aziz Pasha]], died in Zimbabwe. The convicts who were absconding were Abdul Majid, [[Khandaker Abdur Rashid]], [[Noor Chowdhury]],  Risaldar [[Moslehuddin Khan]], [[Rashed Chowdhury]], and [[Shariful Haque Dalim]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Bangabandhu\u2019s killer Abdul Majed arrested |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/dhaka/2020/04/07/bangabandhu-s-killer-abdul-majed-arrested |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=Dhaka Tribune |date=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=6 Killers of Bangabandhu: No progress in bringing them back |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/6-killers-bangabandhu-no-progress-bringing-them-back-1448734 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Daily Star |date=15 August 2017 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the Government of Bangladesh confiscated his properties in Bangladesh, which included 1.35 acre in [[Borhanuddin Municipality]] in [[Bhola District]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Property of Bangabandhu's killer confiscated |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/country/property-bangabandhus-killer-confiscated-128866 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Daily Star |date=19 August 2015 |language=en}}</ref> On 28 August 2008, he was sentenced to life imprisonment in the jail killing case.<ref name=\"starmid\"></ref>\n\nMajed was arrested on 8 April 2020 from [[Mirpur Model Thana|Mirpur]] by [[Counter Terrorism and Transnational Crime]] of [[Dhaka Metropolitan Police]]. He was sent to [[Dhaka Central Jail, Keraniganj]] by a court in Dhaka. He told Bangladesh police officers that he had been hiding in [[Kolkata]] for the last 23 years.<ref name=\"starlast\">{{cite news |title=Bangabandhu Killing: Convicted killer held, sent to jail |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/news/bangabandhu-killing-convicted-killer-held-sent-jail-1890733 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Daily Star |date=8 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u2018Majed was hiding in Kolkata for 23 years\u2019 |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/bangubandhu-killer-abdul-majed-was-hiding-in-kolkata-23-years-1890502 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Daily Star |date=7 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bangladesh arrests fugitive in killing of independence leader |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/world-digest-april-7-2020/2020/04/07/e2acdc96-78d9-11ea-b6ff-597f170df8f8_story.html |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=washingtonpost |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Military of Bangladesh}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Majid, Abdul}}\n[[Category:Assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Army officers]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi military personnel]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Abdul Majed\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = <!--{{Birth date|1950|5|5}}-->\n| birth_place   = Batamara, Borhanudding Upazilla, Bhola\n| death_date    = <!--{{Death date and age|2010|10|10|1950|5|5}}-->\n| occupation    = Military Personel\n| years_active  = \n| allegiance    =\n| branch        = \n| criminal_charges   = <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources -->\n| criminal_penalty   =  \n| criminal_status    = \n| burial_place       = \n| mother             = \n| father             = Ali Mia Chowdhury\n| serviceyears  = \n| rank          = Captain\n}}\n\n'''Abdul Majid''' is a former Bangladesh Army officer who was convicted for his role in the 1975 [[Jail Killing Day|Jail Killing]] following the [[Assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]], the founding father of Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bangabandhu's killer Abdul Majed arrested, sent to jail |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/news/bangabandhus-killer-abdul-majed-arrested-police-1890487 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Dailystar |date=7 April 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news |title=Condemned Mujib killer Majed held |url=https://www.newagebd.net/article/103972/mujib-killer-majed-arrested |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=New Age |language=en}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\n\n==Career==\nAbdul Majed, was a sacked army captain of Bangladesh Army.  Majed was appointed to the Bangladesh Embassy in Senegal. He retired from Bangladesh Army in 1980 and joined the civil administration as a Deputy Secretary. He worked at the [[Bangladesh Inland Water Transport Corporation]]. He was promoted to the rank of Secretary. He joined the Ministry of Youth and Sports as the director of youth development. He was appointed the Director of [[National Savings Directorate]]. He disappeared in 1997 after [[Sheikh Hasina]], daughter of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, was voted Prime Minister of Bangladesh.<ref name=\"starlast\"></ref>\n\n==Conviction==\nOn 14 August 1975, he and other officers looted weapons from Bangal Lancers armory. On 15 August 1975, Sheikh Mujibur Rahman and most of his family members were killed in the [[15 August 1975 Bangladesh coup d'\u00e9tat]]. He meet the other officers met at Bangabhaban and created a new government with [[Khandaker Mushtaq Ahmed]] in charge.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mohiuddin's confession |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/august-15-special-coverage/mohiuddins-confession-1269646 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Daily Star |date=19 November 2009 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Shahriar's confession |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/august-15-special-coverage/shahriars-confession-1269637 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Daily Star |date=19 November 2009 |language=en}}</ref> He was part of the team that attacked the residence of [[Abdur Rab Serniabat]], brother-in-law of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman.<ref>{{cite news |title=No justice yet in 3 other Aug 15 cases |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-150810 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Daily Star |date=15 August 2010 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=FACTBOX: Aug 15 victims |url=https://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/bangabandhu-appeals/2009/11/19/factbox-aug-15-victims |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=bdnews24.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 November 1975, he and the other army officers involved in the assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman meet Khandaker Mushtaq Ahmed at the Bangabhaban. There a decision was made to carry out the [[Jail Killing Day|Jail Killing]] to kill four national leaders of Bangladesh Awami League. The leaders were [[Abul Hasnat Muhammad Qamaruzzaman]], [[Muhammad Mansur Ali]], [[Syed Nazrul Islam]], and [[Tajuddin Ahmed]].<ref name=\"starmid\">{{cite news |title=Mushtaq met all accused on Nov 2 night |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-267225 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Daily Star |date=31 January 2013 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn November 19, 2009, [[Supreme Court of Bangladesh|Bangladesh Supreme Court]] upheld the death sentences of Majed and 11 other self-confessed killers of  Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman. Five of them were executed on January 27, 2010.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bangabandhu Mujibur Rahman's killer Abdul Majed arrested in Bangladesh |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/world/2020/apr/07/bangabandhu-mujibur-rahmans-killer-abdul-majed-arrested-in-bangladesh-2126964.html |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=The New Indian Express |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, he was sentenced to death on the assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman case by a trial court.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Press |first1=Associated |title=Killer of Bangladesh independence leader arrested after 45 years on run |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/07/killer-of-bangladesh-independence-leader-arrested-after-45-years-on-run |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 November 2009, Majed death sentence was confirmed by Bangladesh Supreme Court along with 12 other convicts in the case over the [[Assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]]. Five of the convicts were executed on 27 January 2010. They were [[AKM Mohiuddin Ahmed]], [[Bazlul Huda]], [[Mohiuddin Ahmed]], [[Syed Farooq Rahman]], and [[Sultan Shahriar Rashid Khan]]. Another convict, [[Abdul Aziz Pasha]], died in Zimbabwe. The convicts who were absconding were Abdul Majid, [[Khandaker Abdur Rashid]], [[Noor Chowdhury]],  Risaldar [[Moslehuddin Khan]], [[Rashed Chowdhury]], and [[Shariful Haque Dalim]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Bangabandhu\u2019s killer Abdul Majed arrested |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/dhaka/2020/04/07/bangabandhu-s-killer-abdul-majed-arrested |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=Dhaka Tribune |date=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=6 Killers of Bangabandhu: No progress in bringing them back |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/6-killers-bangabandhu-no-progress-bringing-them-back-1448734 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Daily Star |date=15 August 2017 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the Government of Bangladesh confiscated his properties in Bangladesh, which included 1.35 acre in [[Borhanuddin Municipality]] in [[Bhola District]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Property of Bangabandhu's killer confiscated |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/country/property-bangabandhus-killer-confiscated-128866 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Daily Star |date=19 August 2015 |language=en}}</ref> On 28 August 2008, he was sentenced to life imprisonment in the jail killing case.<ref name=\"starmid\"></ref>\n\nMajed was arrested on 8 April 2020 from [[Mirpur Model Thana|Mirpur]] by [[Counter Terrorism and Transnational Crime]] of [[Dhaka Metropolitan Police]]. He was sent to [[Dhaka Central Jail, Keraniganj]] by a court in Dhaka. He told Bangladesh police officers that he had been hiding in [[Kolkata]] for the last 23 years.<ref name=\"starlast\">{{cite news |title=Bangabandhu Killing: Convicted killer held, sent to jail |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/news/bangabandhu-killing-convicted-killer-held-sent-jail-1890733 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Daily Star |date=8 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u2018Majed was hiding in Kolkata for 23 years\u2019 |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/bangubandhu-killer-abdul-majed-was-hiding-in-kolkata-23-years-1890502 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Daily Star |date=7 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bangladesh arrests fugitive in killing of independence leader |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/world-digest-april-7-2020/2020/04/07/e2acdc96-78d9-11ea-b6ff-597f170df8f8_story.html |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=washingtonpost |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Military of Bangladesh}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Majid, Abdul}}\n[[Category:Assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Army officers]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi military personnel]]\n", "name_user": "Dl2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:reflist auto", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abdul_Majed"}
{"title_page": "Kangra district", "text_new": "{{short description|District in Himachal Pradesh, India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                   = Kangra\n| native_name            = \n| other_name             = Nagarkot , Trigart\n| settlement_type        = [[Districts of Himachal Pradesh|District]]\n| image_skyline          = Kangra.jpg\n| image_caption          = \n| image_map              = HimachalPradeshKangraDistrict.png\n| map_alt                = Located in the northwest part of the state\n| map_caption            = Location in Himachal Pradesh, India\n| pushpin_map            = India\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location in India\n| coordinates            = {{coord|32|13|0|N|76|19|0|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type       = Country\n| subdivision_name       = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1      = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_type2      = [[Tehsil]]s\n| subdivision_name1      = [[Himachal Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_name2      = {{collapsible list|title={{nbsp}}|[[Kangra, Himachal Pradesh|Kangra]]|[[Nurpur, Himachal Pradesh|Nurpur]]|[[Jawali, Himachal Pradesh|Jawali]]|[[Indora]]|[[Dehra]]|Shahpur|[[Baroh]]|[[Khundian]]|[[Jaswan]]|[[Rakkar]]|[[Fatehpur (Vidhan Sabha constituency)]]|[[Baijnath, Himachal Pradesh|Baijnath]]|[[Jaisinghpur]]|[[Dharamsala, Himachal Pradesh|Dharamshala]]|[[Palampur]]}}\n| established_title      = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date       = \n| seat_type              = Headquarters\n| seat                   = [[Dharamsala, Himachal Pradesh|Dharamshala]]\n| leader_title           = [[Member of Parliament, Lok Sabha]]\n| leader_name            = Kishan Kapoor ([[BJP]])\n| leader_title1          = [[Divisional Commissioner]]\n| leader_name1           = Rakesh Kumar Prajapati, IAS\n| leader_title2          = [[Superintendent of Police (India)|Superintendent of Police]]\n| leader_name2           = Vimukt Ranjan, IPS\n| unit_pref              = Metric\n| area_total_km2         = 5739\n| elevation_footnotes    = \n| elevation_m            = \n| population_total       = 1,510,075\n| population_as_of       = 2011\n| population_footnotes   = \n| population_density_km2 = 263\n| timezone1              = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1            = +5:30\n| postal_code_type       = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code            = 176001\n| area_code              = 01892\n| area_code_type         = Telephone\n| blank1_name_sec1       = Largest city\n| blank1_info_sec1       = [[Dharamshala|Dharamsala]] & [[Kangra, Himachal Pradesh|Kangra]]\n| blank1_name_sec2       = [[Climate of India|Climate]]\n| blank1_info_sec2       = [[Climatic regions of India|ETh]] {{small|([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]])}}\n| website                = {{URL|hpkangra.nic.in}}\n| demographics1_info1    = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| blank2_name_sec1       = Gender ratio\n| blank2_info_sec1       = 1012 females/1000 males\n| blank3_name_sec1       = Literacy rate\n| blank3_info_sec1       = 85.67%\n| blank4_name_sec1       = [[List of Constituencies of the Lok Sabha|Lok Sabha Constituency]]\n| blank4_info_sec1       = [[Kangra (Lok Sabha constituency)|Kangra]]\n| blank5_name_sec1       = Vidhan Sabha Constituencies\n| blank5_info_sec1       = {{collapsible list|title={{nbsp}}|[[Nurpur, Himachal Pradesh|Nurpur]]|[[Indora]] (SC)|[[Fatehpur, Kangra|Fatehpur]]|[[Jawali, Himachal Pradesh|Jawali]]|[[Dehra]]|[[Jaswan]]-[[Pragpur]]|[[Jawalamukhi]]|[[Jaisinghpur]] (SC)|[[Sullah]]|[[Nagrota]]|[[Kangra, Himachal Pradesh|Kangra]]|Shahpur|[[Dharamsala, Himachal Pradesh|Dharamshala]]|[[Palampur]]|[[Baijnath, Himachal Pradesh|Baijnath]] (SC)}}\n| blank2_name_sec2       = Avg. summer temperature\n| blank2_info_sec2       = {{convert|32|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}\n| blank3_name_sec2       = Avg. winter temperature\n| blank3_info_sec2       = {{convert|20|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}\n}}\n'''Kangra''' is the most populous<ref name=\"districtcensus\">{{cite web | url = http://www.census2011.co.in/district.php | title = District Census 2011 | accessdate = 30 September 2011 | year = 2011 | publisher = Census2011.co.in}}</ref> [[List of districts of Himachal Pradesh|district]] of the Indian state of [[Himachal Pradesh]]. [[Dharamsala, Himachal Pradesh|Dharamshala]] is the administrative headquarters of the district.\n\n==History==\n{{see also|History of the Punjab|Kangra fort}}\n[[File:Battle of Kangada.webp|thumb|Battle of Kangda led by Nepali commander [[Amar Singh Thapa]]]]\nKangra is known for having the oldest serving Royal Dynasty in the world, the [[Katoch]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2016}} In 1758, Raja Ghamand Chand\nwas appointed ''nazim'' or governor of Jullundur Doab under the Afghans. Ghamand Chand was a brave and strong ruler who restored the prestige of Kangra. As he was unable to capture [[Kangra fort]], he built another fort at Tira Sujanpur on the left bank of the Beas, almost opposite to Alampur on a hill overlooking the town. He died in 1774 and was succeeded by his son, Tegh Chand, who died too soon in 1775.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20180701145502/http://himachalpradeshtravel.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/History-of-Kangra.pdf</ref> Kangra was annexed by Maharaja Ranjit Singh's Sikh Empire in 1810. Kangra became a district of [[British India]] in 1846, when it was ceded to British India at the conclusion of the [[First Anglo-Sikh War]]. The British district included the present-day districts of Kangra, [[Hamirpur District, Himachal Pradesh|Hamirpur]], [[Kullu District|Kullu]], and [[Lahul and Spiti]]. Kangra District was part of the British province of [[Punjab, British India|Punjab]]. The administrative headquarters of the district were initially at Kangra, but were moved to [[Dharamsala, Himachal Pradesh|Dharamshala]] in 1855.<ref>[http://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V14_386.gif Kangra District] ''[[The Imperial Gazetteer of India]]'', v. 14, p. 380.</ref><ref>[http://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V11_307.gif Dharamshala] ''[[The Imperial Gazetteer of India]]'', v. 11, p. 301.</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{bar box\n|title=Religions in Kangra District\n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|96.76}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|01.31}}\n{{bar percent|[[Buddhist]]|red|0.96}}\n{{bar percent|[[Sikhs]]|black|0.59}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christians]]|Yellow|0.20}}\n{{bar percent|Others|green|0.17}}\n|}}\n\nAccording to the [[2011 census of India|2011 census]] Kangra district had population of {{sigfig|1510075|3}}.<ref name=\"2011CensusHandbook\"/>{{rp|18}}\n\nAt the 2011 Census, 70.9% of the population in the district declared their first language to be [[Kangri language|Kangri]], 14.9% opted for [[Pahari languages|Pahari]], 5.55% \u2013 [[Hindi]], 2.64% \u2013 [[Bharmauri language|Bharmauri]], 2.06% \u2013 [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]], 0.81% \u2013 [[Tibetan languages|Tibetan]], 0.71% \u2013 [[Dogri language|Dogri]], and 0.54% [[Nepali language|Nepali]] as their first language.<ref>{{cite web |title=C-16 Population By Mother Tongue - Himachal Pradesh |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/C-16/DDW-C16-STMT-MDDS-0200.XLSX |website=censusindia.gov.in |accessdate=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''District Highlights of 2011 Census'''<ref name=\"2011CensusHandbook\">{{Cite web|url=http://censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/0202_PART_B_DCHB_KANGRA.pdf|title=DISTRICT CENSUS HANDBOOK KANGRAVILLAGE AND TOWN WISEPRIMARY CENSUS ABSTRACT (PCA)|website=censusindia.gov.in/2011census|access-date=18 September 2018}}</ref>\n* Kangra district has the highest number of 3,869 villages among the 12 district of the state.\n* Kangra district occupies the 1st rank among the districts in terms of population.\n* Kangra district occupies the 2nd position in terms of sex ratio among the districts of the state with 1,012 females per 1,000 males as compared to 972 females per 1,000 males of state average.\n* Kangra district stands 1st position in terms of its working force having total workers of 675,170 persons against 3,559,422 working persons of the state.\n* Kangra district stands at 5th positions in terms of decadal population growth (2001-2011) of 12.8 per cent persons in comparison to state decadal population growth of 12.9 per cent persons.\n* In terms of density of population per km<sup>2</sup>., Kangra district with 263 persons per km<sup>2</sup>. stands at 5th rank in the state.\n* Kangra district occupies 1st rank among the districts of the state in terms of literate population. It has a literate population of 1,152,640 persons.\n* Kangra district holds the 2nd rank in terms of scheduled tribe population in the state. It has reported 84,564 persons as scheduled tribe.\n* The economy of Kangra district is mainly depends on agriculture. It has returned 303,007 persons as cultivators and holds the 2nd position among the districts of the state\n* All the inhabited villages of the district enjoy the facility of electricity and potable drinking water.\n* Kangra district is also known for its attractive tourist destinations. [[Dharamsala]], [[Kangra, Himachal Pradesh|Kangra]], [[Palampur]], [[Baijnath, Himachal Pradesh|Baijnath]], [[Jawalamukhi]] and [[Masroor]] are the famous places of tourist interest in the district. McLeodganj in Dharamsala is a seat of the Dalai Lama has become a place of international fame since 1966.\n* Central University of Himachal Pradesh at Dharamsala in Kangra district was established on 20 March 2009 under the Central University Act 2009(No.25 of 2009) of Indian Parliament.\n\nThe native people are the [[Kangri people]] and the native language is [[Kangri language|Kangri]], which is very similar to [[Dogri language|Dogri]].  The majority of the people are [[Hindu]] [[Brahmin]], [[Rajput]], [[Chaudhary]],  [[Banias|Jat]],[[Banias]] and SC/OBC, although many [[Tibetan people|Tibetans]] and others who follow [[Buddhism]] have also settled here recently. There are also minority populations of Sikhs, Muslims, and Christians.\n\nJhamakda is a folk dance of Kangra. It is exclusively performed by women. It features percussion instruments and songs.<ref>http://himachalpradeshtravel.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/History-of-Kangra.pdf</ref>{{historical populations|11=1901|12=4,78,364|13=1911|14=4,69,046|15=1921|16=4,69,251|17=1931|18=4,94,658|19=1941|20=5,63,163|21=1951|22=5,70,643|23=1961|24=6,57,232|25=1971|26=8,00,863|27=1981|28=9,90,758|29=1991|30=11,74,072|31=2001|32=13,39,030|33=2011|34=15,10,075|percentages=pagr|footnote=source:<ref>[http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/A2_Data_Table.html Decadal Variation In Population Since 1901]</ref>|align=middle}}\n\n==Education==\n* [[Central University of Himachal Pradesh]] \n* [[College for Higher Tibetan Studies, Sarah]]\n* [[Government College of Teacher Education Dharamsala]]\n\n===Schools===\n* [[Jawahar Navodaya Vidyalaya, Kangra]]\n* [[Sacred Heart Sr. Sec. School (Sidhpur)]]\n* [[Sherab Gatsel Lobling School]]\n\n==Notable People From Kangra District==\n\n* [[Shanta Kumar]] - Indian Politician\n* [[Kishan Kapoor]] - Indian Politician\n* [[G. S. Bali]] - Indian Politician\n* [[Sudhir Sharma]] - Indian Politician\n* [[Chander Kumar]] - Indian Politician\n* [[Karnail Rana]] - Himachali Folk Singer\n* [[Ajay Saklani]] - producer, director & DOP\n* [[Anuj Sharma]] - singer, second Indian ''Idol'' runner-up\n* [[Shriya Sharma]] - film actress\n* [[Shivya Pathania]] - television actress\n\n==Climate==\nIt is situated in Western Himalayas between latitude 31\u00b02\u0384-32\u00b05\u0384 N,longitude 75\u00b0-75\u00b045\u0384 E. The elevation above the sea level of Kangra district is in the range of 427 to 6,401 meters. The district is spread over 5,739&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> having about 216643 hectare of land, out of which 195738 hectare is under cultivation. In this district, river Beas flows through distance of 94.00&nbsp;km. The soil characteristic is both sandy & loamy. The climate of district is pleasant around the year except in plains like Nurpur, Indora, Fatehpur areas where temperature may raise up to 40&nbsp;\u00b0C in the month of May/June. Monsoon sets in the first week of July and continues till mid September.<ref>http://www.entomoljournal.com/archives/2016/vol4issue4/PartI/4-4-3-508.pdf</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Agahar]]\n* [[Chambi, Himachal Pradesh]]\n* [[Dhanotu]]\n* [[Kangra Valley]]\n* [[Kangra Valley Railway]]\n* [[Kangra Fort]]\n* [[Kangra painting]]\n* [[List of India cave temples]]\n* [[List of caves#India|List of Caves in India]]\n* [[List of rock-cut temples in India]]\n* [[Indian rock-cut architecture]]\n* [[List of colossal sculpture in situ]]\n* [[Pit cave]]\n* [[Shamirpur]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Hutchinson, J. & J. PH Vogel (1933). ''History of the Panjab Hill States'', Vol. I. 1st edition: Govt. Printing, Punjab, Lahore, 1933. Reprint 2000. Department of Language and Culture, Himachal Pradesh. Chapter V Kangra State, pp.&nbsp;99\u2013198.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Kangra}}\n* {{Official website|hpkangra.nic.in}} - Kangra District\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101125203959/http://himachalpr.gov.in/intranet/Kangra/Distt%20Profile.doc Distt Profile]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101125204103/http://himachalpr.gov.in/intranet/Kangra/Kangra's%20History.doc Kangra's History]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101125203758/http://himachalpr.gov.in/intranet/Kangra/Temples%20of%20Kangra.doc Temples of Kangra]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101125203850/http://himachalpr.gov.in/intranet/Kangra/Kangra%20Map.jpg Kangra Map]\n\n{{Geographic location\n| Centre    = Kangra district\n| North     = [[Chamba district]]\n| Northeast = [[Lahaul and Spiti district]]\