1 || 1 || 10 || 0 || 0 || 3 November 2019\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{cr|IRE}} || 5 || 3 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 18 July 2012\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{cr|NZL}} || 7 || 0 || 7 || 0 || 0 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{cr|PAK}} || 12 || 2 || 10 || 0 || 0 || 24 April 2015\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{cr|RSA}} || 6 || 0 || 6 || 0 || 0 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{cr|SRI}} || 11 || 4 || 7 || 0 || 0 || 28 February 2016\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{cr|WIN}} || 12 || 5 || 6 || 0 || 1 || 13 September 2007\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{cr|ZIM}} || 13 || 9 || 4 || 0 || 0 || 28 November 2006\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''v. Associate Members'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{cr|HK}} || 1 || 0 || 1 || 0 || 0 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{cr|KEN}} || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 1 September 2007\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{cr|NEP}} || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 18 March 2014\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{cr|NED}} || 3 || 2 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 25 July 2012\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{cr|OMN}} || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 13 March 2016\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{cr|SCO}} || 1 || 0 || 1 || 0 || 0 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{cr|UAE}} || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 26 February 2016\n|}\n* Players listed in '''bold''' are still playing. \n''Records complete to T20I #1084. Last updated 11 March 2020.''\n\n==World records==\n===As a team===\n\n* Most consecutive Test defeats 21 (2001\u20132004).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/284055.html |title=Records / Test matches / Team records / Most consecutive defeats |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |accessdate=20 July 2015}}</ref>\n* Most consecutive Test series defeats 16 (2000/01-2004/05).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283964.html |title=Records / Test matches / Team records / Most consecutive series defeats |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |accessdate=20 July 2015}}</ref>\n* Most consecutive ODI defeats 23 (1999\u20132002).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/Ci/content/records/284056.html |title=Records / One-Day Internationals / Team records / Most consecutive defeats |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |accessdate=20 July 2015}}</ref>\n* Most consecutive ODIs without victory 47 (1999\u20132003).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/284049.html |title=Records / One-Day Internationals / Team records / Most consecutive matches without victory |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |accessdate=20 July 2015}}</ref>\n* Only Test side which have lost the first ODI they have played against five non-Test sides (Canada 2003, Kenya 2003, Ireland 2007, Netherlands 2010 and Afghanistan 2014).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/asia-cup-2014/content/story/724301.html |title=Bangladesh's first-encounter |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=March 2014 |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref>\n* The highest innings total in a losing cause 595/8 dec vs New Zealand in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/18485552/highest-total-losing-cause |title = Bangladesh's 595: The highest total in a losing cause|date = 16 January 2017}}</ref>\n* Bangladesh has taken 16 years and 12 days\u2014the least amount of time among all 10 Test-playing countries\u2014to reach the landmark figure of playing 100 tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/cricket/youngest-test-side-bangladesh-cricket-team-set-for-century-milestone/story-Zhq4yrpKYbI8yRJ4RBFI6M.html |title=Youngest Test side Bangladesh cricket team set for century milestone |work=Hindustan Times |date=14 March 2017 |accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n* Only test side which have not been involved in any tied international matches.\n\n===By Bangladeshi players===\n* [[Aminul Islam (cricketer, born 1968)|Aminul Islam]] became the third cricketer to score a century on their country's inaugural test in 2000 against [[Indian national cricket team|India]]. He achieved this feat after [[Charles Bannerman]] ([[Australia national cricket team|Australia]]) and [[David Houghton (cricketer)|Dave Houghton]] ([[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]]) while [[Ireland cricket team|Irish cricketer]] [[Kevin O'Brien (cricketer)|Kevin O'Brien]] was the latest and the fourth member to join this elite club.<ref name=\"BAN18yrsRecord\">{{citation |url=https://www.prothomalo.com/sports/article/1564616/%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%82%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%A6%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B6%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%A4-%E0%A6%A4%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%A4%E0%A7%8B-%E0%A6%AE%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%A0%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B6%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AC-%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A1 |title=Some bitter-sweet records of Bangladeh cricket team in test |work=[[Prothom Alo]] |accessdate= 10 November 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Mohammad Ashraful]] holds the record for the youngest cricketer to make a Test century. He was 17 years and 61 days old when he made 114 against [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]] at [[Sinhalese Sports Club Ground|Colombo]] on 8 September 2001, during his Test debut.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/282986.html|title=Records {{!}} Test matches {{!}} Batting records {{!}} Youngest player to score a hundred {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=Cricinfo|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n* In 2005 against [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]], [[Enamul Haque (Sylhet cricketer, born 1986)|Enamul Haque Jr.]] became the youngest bowler ever to take a 10 wicket-haul in test at the age of 18 years 40 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283789.html|title=Records {{!}} Test matches {{!}} Bowling records {{!}} Youngest player to take ten-wickets-in-a-match {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=Cricinfo|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n* [[Mashrafe Mortaza]] was the leading wicket-taker in [[One Day International|ODI]]s in 2006, with 49 wickets in 27 matches.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?class=2;id=2006;type=year |title=Records / 2006 / One-Day Internationals / Most wickets |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref>\n* On 21 November 2012, [[Abul Hasan (cricketer)|Abul Hasan]] became only the second Test cricketer in history to make a century at number 10 on debut, against the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]] at [[Sheikh Abu Naser Stadium|Khulna]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/duff-peer-bangladesh-cricketer-equals-110yearold-test-record-20121121-29rbr.html |title=Duff peer: Bangladesh cricketer equals 110-year-old Test record |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=22 November 2012| accessdate=26 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-west-indies-2012/content/story/592201.html |title = No. 10 Abul Hasan's debut ton revives Bangladesh|date = 21 November 2012}}</ref>\n* On 13 October 2013, against [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]] at [[Zohur Ahmed Chowdhury Stadium|Chittagong]], [[Sohag Gazi]] became the first cricketer ever to score a century and take a hat-trick in the same Test match.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-new-zealand-2013-14/content/story/679189.html |title=Gazi shines as Test ends in draw |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=13 October 2013 |accessdate=13 December 2014}}</ref>\n* In 2014, [[Shakib Al Hasan]] became only third cricketer after [[Ian Botham]] ([[England cricket team|England]]) and [[Imran Khan]] ([[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]]) to score a century and to pick up 10 wickets in same test.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/287370.html|title=Records {{!}} Test matches {{!}} All-round records {{!}} 100 runs and 10 wickets in a match {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=Cricinfo|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n* [[Taijul Islam]] became the first bowler ever to take a hat-trick on debut in an ODI against [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]] at [[Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium|Dhaka]] on 1 December 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-zimbabwe-2014-15/content/story/806027.html |title=Taijul debut hat-trick seals 5\u20130 win |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=1 December 2014 |accessdate=1 December 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Shakib Al Hasan]] became the first player in history to hold the number 1 positions in all three formats of cricket, in the all-rounder category on 12 January 2015.<ref name=\"news.com.au\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.prothom-alo.com/sport/news/57883/Shakib-top-all-rounder-in-all-3-formats |title=Shakib top all-rounder in all 3 formats |work=Prothom Alo |accessdate=9 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310181901/http://en.prothom-alo.com/sport/news/57883/Shakib-top-all-rounder-in-all-3-formats |archive-date=10 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Mustafizur Rahman]] became the first cricketer ever to take 11 wickets in his first two ODIs when he took 5/50 against [[India national cricket team|India]] on 18 June 2015 and then 6/43 against the same team three days later. Both matches were played at Dhaka.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-india-2015/content/story/890051.html |title=Mustafizur's record-breaking ODI genesis |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=21 June 2015 |accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref>\n* Until 25 July 2015, [[Elias Sunny]] was the only player to be nominated as the Man of the match in two formats of the international cricket as a debutant. He made it in Test(v [[West Indies national cricket team|West Indies]] in 2011) & T20I(v [[Ireland national cricket team|Ireland]] in 2012).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/531986.html |title=Test debutant Sunny became Player of the match |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=25 October 2011 |accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/531986.html |title=T20I debutant Sunny became Player of the match |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=18 July 2012 |accessdate=19 July 2012}}</ref> [[Mustafizur Rahman]], being only second to Elias Sunny, did it in ODI(v [[India national cricket team|India]]) and in Test(v [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]]) both in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bangla.bdnews24.com/cricket/article1001610.bdnews |title=\u09ae\u09c1\u09b8\u09cd\u09a4\u09be\u09ab\u09bf\u099c\u09c7\u09b0 \u0985\u09a8\u09a8\u09cd\u09af \u0987\u09a4\u09bf\u09b9\u09be\u09b8 |publisher=[[bdnews24.com]] |date=25 July 2015 |accessdate=26 July 2015}}</ref>\n* On 7 June 2018 in the 3rd T20I against [[Afghan national cricket team|Afghanistan]] by taking the wicket of [[Najibullah Zadran]], [[Shakib Al Hasan]] became the quickest All-rounder to achieve the double of 10,000 runs and 500 wickets in 302 international matches and became only 3rd cricketer to do so following [[Jacques Kallis]] and [[Shahid Afridi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.sportskeeda.com/cricket/stats-shakib-al-hasan-fastest-to-register-10-000-runs-and-500-wickets-in-international-cricket-history|title=Shakib became the quickest All-rounder to achieve the double of 10000 runs & 500 wickets}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cricket|Bangladesh}} \n* [[Bangladesh Premier League]] \n* [[Bangladesh national women's cricket team]] \n* [[List of Bangladesh national cricket captains]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{commons category|Bangladesh national cricket team}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.tigercricket.com.bd}}\n{{Asian Games cricket men's tournament winners}}\n{{Bangladesh national cricket team}} \n{{National sports teams of Bangladesh}} \n{{International cricket tours of Bangladesh}}  \n{{National cricket teams}}\n\n[[Category:Cricket in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:National cricket teams|Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:National sports teams of Bangladesh|Cricket]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh in international cricket]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the men's team|the women's team|Bangladesh women's national cricket team}}\n{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox cricket team\n| name                  = Bangladesh\n| image                 = Flag of Bangladesh.svg\n| alt                   = Refer to caption\n| caption               = Flag of Bangladesh\n| association           = [[Bangladesh Cricket Board]]\n| nickname\t\t= The Tigers \n| test_captain          = [[Mominul Haque]]\n| od_captain            = [[Tamim Iqbal]]\n| t20i_captain          = [[Mahmudullah]]\n| coach                 = [[Russell Domingo]] \n| test_status_year      = 2000\n\n| icc_status            = Associate Member\n| icc_member_year       = 1977\n| icc_status2           = [[List of International Cricket Council members#Full Member|Full Member]]\n| icc_member_year2      = 2000\n| icc_region            = [[Asian Cricket Council|Asia]]\n\n| test_rank             = 9th\n| odi_rank              = 7th\n| t20i_rank             = 9th\n| test_rank_best        = 8th <ref>{{cite news|title=Bangladesh rise to no 8 in ICC test rankings|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/sport/cricket/2018/05/01/bangladesh-rise-no-8-icc-test-ranking/|work=Dhaka Tribiune|date=1 May 2018 |accessdate=11 March 2020}} </ref>\n| odi_rank_best         = 6th <ref>{{cite news|title=Bangladesh rise no 6 in odi rankings|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/19461070/bangladesh-rise-no-6-odi-rankings|work=[[ESPNcricinfo]]|date= 25 May 2017|accessdate=11 March 2020}}\n</ref>\n| t20i_rank_best        = 4th <ref>{{cite news|title=Bangladesh to play extra T20 in Netherlands|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ireland-nl-v-bangladesh-2012/content/story/573750.html|work=[[ESPNcricinfo]]|date=24 July 2012|accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n| first_test            = v. {{cr|IND}} at [[Bangabandhu National Stadium]], [[Dhaka]]; 10\u201313 November 2000\n| most_recent_test      = v. {{cr|ZIM}} at [[Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium]], [[Dhaka]];22\u201325 February 2020\n| num_tests             = 119\n| num_tests_this_year   = 2\n| test_record           = 14/89<br />(16 draws)\n| test_record_this_year = 1/1 (0 draws)\n\n| first_odi             = v. {{cr|PAK}} at [[De Soysa Stadium|Tyronne Fernando Stadium]], [[Moratuwa]]; 31 March 1986\n| most_recent_odi       = v. {{cr|ZIM}} at [[Sylhet International Cricket Stadium]], [[Sylhet]]; 6 March 2020\n| num_odis              = 376\n| num_odis_this_year    = 3\n| odi_record            = 128/241<br />(0 ties, 7 no result)\n| odi_record_this_year  = 3/0<br />(0 ties, 0 no result)\n\n| wc_apps               = 6\n| wc_first              = [[1999 Cricket World Cup|1999]] \n| wc_best               = Quarter-final ([[2015 Cricket World Cup|2015]])\n| wcq_apps              = 6\n| wcq_first             = [[1979 ICC Trophy|1979]]\n| wcq_best              = {{GoldMedal}} Champions ([[1997 ICC Trophy|1997]])\n\n| first_t20i            = v. {{cr|ZIM}} at [[Sheikh Abu Naser Stadium]], [[Khulna]]; 28 November 2006\n| most_recent_t20i      = v. {{cr|ZIM}} at [[Sher-e-Bangla National Stadium]], [[Dhaka]]; 11 March 2020\n| num_t20is             = 96\n| num_t20is_this_year   = 4\n| t20i_record           = 32/62<br />(0 ties, 2 no results)\n| t20i_record_this_year = 2/2<br />(0 ties, 0 no results)\n\n| wt20_apps             = 6\n| wt20_first            = [[2007 ICC World Twenty20|2007]]\n| wt20_best             = 2nd round (2007, [[2014 ICC World Twenty20|2014]], [[2016 ICC World Twenty20|2016]])\n\n| h_pattern_la          = \n| h_pattern_b           = _collar\n| h_pattern_ra          = \n| h_pattern_pants       = \n| h_leftarm             = \n| h_body                = \n| h_rightarm            = \n| h_pants               = \n| a_pattern_la          = \n| a_pattern_b           = _red_halfshoulders\n| a_pattern_ra          = \n| a_pattern_pants       = \n| a_leftarm             = 003300\n| a_body                = 005400\n| a_rightarm            = 003300\n| a_pants               = 003300\n| a_title               = ODI and T20I kit\n\n| asofdate              = 11 March 2020\n}}\n\nThe '''Bangladesh men's national cricket team''' ({{lang-bn|\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u0995\u09cd\u09b0\u09bf\u0995\u09c7\u099f \u09a6\u09b2}}), popularly known as '''The Tigers'''<ref>{{cite news|title= Bangladesh Tigers come of age|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/tms/2007/04/bangladesh_tigers_come_of_age.shtml|work=BBC|date=7 April 2007|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>, is administered by the [[Bangladesh Cricket Board]] (BCB). It is a [[List of International Cricket Council members#Full Member|Full Member]] of the [[International Cricket Council]] (ICC) with [[Test cricket|Test]] , [[One-Day International]] (ODI) and [[T20 International]] (T20I) status. It played [[Indian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2000\u201301|its first Test match]] in November 2000 against [[India national cricket team|India]] in [[Dhaka]], becoming the tenth Test-playing nation.\n\nBangladesh's first official foray into international cricket came in the [[1979 ICC Trophy]] in England. On 31 March 1986, Bangladesh played its first ODI match, against [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]] in the [[1986 Asia Cup|Asia Cup]]. For a long time, [[Association football|football]] was the most popular sport in Bangladesh, but cricket gradually became very popular \u2013 particularly in urban areas \u2013 and by the late 1990s had surpassed football. [[File:Bangladesh national cricket team 1986.jpg|260x260px|thumb|Bangladesh made its full debut in international cricket in the 1986 Asia Cup.|alt=]]\n\nIn 1997, Bangladesh won the [[1997 ICC Trophy|ICC Trophy]] in Malaysia and thus qualified for its first [[Cricket World Cup]] to participate in England in [[1999 Cricket World Cup|1999]]. There, it defeated [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]] \u2013 causing much upset \u2013 and also [[Scotland national cricket team|Scotland]]. On 26 June 2000, Bangladesh was granted full ICC membership.\n\nBangladesh holds the record for most consecutive losses in Tests (21, between 2000 and 2002) and ODIs (23, between 2001 and 2004). After gaining Full Member status with the ICC, Bangladesh had to wait until 2004 for its first ODI win since the 1999 World Cup. The team on the losing side on that occasion was [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]], who also participated in Bangladesh's maiden Test victory in 2005; by securing a draw in the second match, Bangladesh won their first Test series. In 2009 Bangladesh toured the West Indies for two Tests and by winning both secured their first overseas Test series victory.\n\nAs of 20 June 2019, Bangladesh has played 114 Tests, winning thirteen. Its first victory was against team Zimbabwe, and the next two came against the West Indian team. Results have improved predominantly at home with draws earned against New Zealand, Pakistan, India and South Africa and wins against England, Sri Lanka and Australia.<ref name=\"Testlist\">{{citation |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/team/25.html?class=1;template=results;type=team;view=results |title=Statsguru&nbsp;\u2013 Bangladesh&nbsp;\u2013 Test matches&nbsp;\u2013 Team analysis |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref> They played their 100th Test when they [[Bangladeshi cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2016\u201317|toured Sri Lanka]] in March 2017.<ref name=\"Bang100\">{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/1083021.html |title=Bangladesh to play 100th Test in March |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=17 February 2017 |accessdate=17 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe team has been more successful in ODIs, having won 124 of its 367 matches.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/team/25.html?class=2;template=results;type=team;view=results |title=Statsguru&nbsp;\u2013 Bangladesh&nbsp;\u2013 ODI matches&nbsp;\u2013 Team analysis |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=24 May 2017}}</ref> It has also played 85 [[Twenty20 International]]s, winning 26.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/team/25.html?class=3;template=results;type=team;view=results |title=Statsguru&nbsp;\u2013 Bangladesh&nbsp;\u2013 T20I matches&nbsp;\u2013 Team analysis |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh is currently ranked 9th in Tests, 7th in ODIs and 9th in T20Is by the ICC.<ref name=\"ICCrankings\">{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/rankings/content/page/211271.html |title=ICC rankings \u2013 ICC Test, ODI and Twenty20 rankings |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |accessdate=21 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of cricket in Bangladesh}}\n\n===20th century===\nSeveral [[East Pakistan]]-based sides played in Pakistani domestic cricket prior to Bangladesh's declaration of independence of 1971\u2014the [[East Pakistan cricket team]] fielded [[List of East Pakistan first-class cricketers|three players]] who later played [[ICC Trophy]] matches. In 1977, Bangladesh became an Associate member of the [[International Cricket Council]] (ICC).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/about/members/asia/full/22|title=Bangladesh|work=[[International Cricket Council|ICC]]|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> Bangladesh was one of fifteen teams to take part in the inaugural [[1979 ICC Trophy|ICC Trophy]]. Held in 1979, it gave non-Test playing countries the opportunity to qualify for that year's [[1979 Cricket World Cup|World Cup]]. Bangladesh, under the captaincy of [[Raqibul Hasan (cricketer, born 1953)|Raqibul Hasan]], won two matches and lost two, but failed to progress beyond the first round.<ref>{{citation |url=http://static.espncricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/WORLD_CUPS/ICCT79/ICCT79_TABLES.html |title=ICCT79: Final Group Tables |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://static.espncricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/WORLD_CUPS/ICCT79/ICCT79_PREVIEW |title=ICCT79: Preview |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref> Victory in the South-East Asian Cricket Conference Tournament in February 1984 ensured Bangladesh qualified for the [[1986 Asia Cup]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/154346.html |title=Asia Cup, 1985\u201386 |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref> On 31 March 1986, Bangladesh played their first One Day International against a [[List of International Cricket Council members#Full Member|Full Member]] of the ICC;<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/150618.html |title=Asia Cup: Bangladesh v Pakistan 1985\u201386 |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref>\n{{Limited overs international\n| date = 31 March 1986\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|BAN}}\n| score1 = 94 all out (35.3 overs)\n| score2 = 98/3 (32.1 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| runs1 = [[Shaheedur Rahman]] 37 (60)\n| wickets1 = [[Wasim Akram]] 4/19 (9 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Mudassar Nazar]] 47 (97)\n| wickets2 = [[Jahangir Shah]] 2/23 (9 overs)\n| result = {{cr|PAK}} won by 7 wickets\n| report = [http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/47/47028.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Tyronne Fernando Stadium]], [[Moratuwa]], Sri Lanka\n| umpires = [[Herbi Felsinger]] (SL) and [[PW Vidanagamage]] (SL)\n| motm = [[Wasim Akram]]\n}}\nCaptained by [[Gazi Ashraf]], Bangladesh were dismissed for 94 and Pakistan reached their target for victory with seven wickets in hand.<ref>{{citation  |url-access=subscription |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/47/47028.html |title=a4779 o375 Bangladesh v Pakistan: John Player Gold Leaf Trophy (Asia Cup) 1985/86 |publisher=CricketArchive.com |accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref> They lost their second ODI, which was against Sri Lanka, finishing last in the three-team tournament.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Seasons/SL/1985-86_SL_John_Player_Gold_Leaf_Trophy_%28Asia_Cup%29_1985-86.html |title=John Player Gold Leaf Trophy (Asia Cup) 1985/86 |publisher=CricketArchive.com |accessdate=15 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611180109/http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Seasons/SL/1985-86_SL_John_Player_Gold_Leaf_Trophy_%28Asia_Cup%29_1985-86.html |archivedate=11 June 2011  }}</ref> Bangladesh qualified for the [[1988 Asia Cup]], this time hosting the tournament; it was the first time ODIs had been staged in the country. Although they lost all their matches, Bangladesh's fixtures were retrospectively awarded ODI. Floods in the preceding months meant the tournament was in doubt, but it went ahead as planned. A charity match raised $70,000 for the flood victims.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/155174.html |title=Asia Cup, 1988\u201389 |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref> Bangladesh added a black mark in [[1986 ICC Trophy]] with only 2 wins.\n\nBangladesh took part in the [[Austral-Asia Cup|1990 Austral-Asia Cup]],<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/150808.html |title=Austral-Asia Cup, 1989\u201390 |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref> the Asia Cup in [[1990\u201391 Asia Cup|1990\u201391]], [[1995 Asia Cup|1995]],<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/151185.html |title=Pepsi Asia Cup, 1994\u201395 |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref> [[1997 Asia Cup|1997]],<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/151650.html |title=Pepsi Asia Cup, 1997\u201398 |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref> and several other triangular tournaments, but it was not until 1998 that they won their first ODI. Their 22-match losing streak since their first ODI was at the time a record.<ref name=\"toothless tigers\">{{citation |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/cwc2003/hi/newsid_2570000/newsid_2573000/2573035.stm |title=Toothless Tigers |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2 January 2003 |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> \n{{Limited overs international\n| date = 17 May 1998\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|KEN}}\n| score1 = 236 all out (49 overs)\n| score2 = 237/4 (48 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|BAN}}\n| runs1 = [[Ravi Shah]] 52 (64)\n| wickets1 = [[Mohammad Rafique (cricketer)|Mohammad Rafique]] 3/56 (10 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Mohammad Rafique (cricketer)|Mohammad Rafique]] 77 (87)\n| wickets2 = [[Mohammad Sheikh]] 2/46 (10 overs)\n| result = {{cr|BAN}} won by 6 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8559/scorecard/66145/Bangladesh-vs-Kenya-2nd-Match-coca-cola-triangular-series/ Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Lal Bahadur Shastri Stadium]], [[Hyderabad]], India\n| umpires = [[SK Sharma]] (Ind) and [[C. R. Mohite]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/65/65757.html |title=Bangladesh v Kenya in 1997/98 |date=17 May 1998 |website=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> (Ind)\n| motm = [[Mohammad Rafique (cricketer)|Mohammad Rafique]]\n}}\nBangladesh posted its first ODI win against Kenya, in India thanks largely to [[Mohammad Rafique (cricketer)|Mohammad Rafique]], who contributed a fiery 77 runs and took 3 wickets. Put on 137 for the first wicket with [[Athar Ali Khan]]. Athar's own contribution was 47.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/66145.html scorecard]: Bangladesh v Kenya (17 May 1998), Retrieved on (27 January 2008)</ref>\n\nIn October 1998, Bangladesh hosted (but did not participate in) the first [[1998 ICC KnockOut Trophy|ICC KnockOut Trophy]] ever held (the event later became the ICC Champions Trophy), a knock-out ODI tournament featuring all the Test playing nations.\n\nBangladesh took part in each of the [[1979 ICC Trophy|1979]], [[1982 ICC Trophy|1982]], [[1986 ICC Trophy|1986]], [[1990 ICC Trophy|1990]], and [[1994 ICC Trophy|1994]] editions of the ICC Trophy, and won the trophy in [[1997 ICC Trophy|1997]], in the process qualified for the 1999 World Cup. The then General Secretary of Bangladesh Cricket Board, [[Aminul Huq Moni]] took the initiative to install [[AstroTurf|Astro Turf]] in [[Abahani Limited (Dhaka)|Abahani]] Cricket Ground and [[Bangabandhu National Stadium]], so that the local players had two full seasons to prepare on the type of pitch they would playing in ICC Trophy in 1997.<ref>{{cite news|title = Former BCB general secretary dies in Dhaka|url = http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/883039.html|work = ESPNcricinfo |date=1 June 2015 |access-date = 16 January 2016}}</ref> Bangladesh also became a regular ICC member with the right to play ODIs and started hosting bilateral and triangular ODI tournaments. Earlier, in February Dhaka hosted the third and final SAARC cricket tournament. Bangladesh played in its first World Cup in England in 1999 and recorded their first win in a World Cup match against Scotland. Later Bangladesh created an enormous upset by beating [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]] by 62 runs in the group match at [[County Ground, Northampton|Northampton]].\n{{Single-innings cricket match\n| date = 31 May 1999\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|BAN}}\n| score1 = 223/9 (50 overs)\n| score2 = 161 (44.3 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| runs1 = [[Akram Khan (cricketer)|Akram Khan]] 42 (66)\n| wickets1 = [[Saqlain Mushtaq]] 5/35 (10 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Wasim Akram]] 29 (52)\n| wickets2 = [[Khaled Mahmud]] 3/31 (10 overs)\n| result = Bangladesh won by 62 runs\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/65221.html Scorecard]\n| venue = County Ground, Northampton, England\n| umpires = [[Doug Cowie (umpire)|Doug Cowie]] (NZ) and [[Darrell Hair]] (Aus)\n| motm = [[Khaled Mahmud]] (Ban)\n| toss = \n| rain = \n| notes = \n}}\nBangladesh made 9/223 from its full 50 overs, and in reply, Pakistan could only manage 161 due to timely run-outs by wicket-keeper [[Khaled Mashud]] and some tight bowling by [[Khaled Mahmud]], who took 3/31 from 10 overs. Mahmud was judged the man of the match. Bangladesh did not qualify for the Super Six round due to defeats in three of its five matches. However, the win over Pakistan, who finished runners-up to [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]], helped Bangladesh to gain Test playing status the following year. Bangladesh had sacked coach [[Gordon Greenidge]], who had steered the team through the [[1997 ICC Trophy]] and into the [[1999 Cricket World Cup|1999 World Cup]] on the morning of the match.<ref name=\"toothless tigers\"/>\n\nFormer South Africa Test cricketer [[Eddie Barlow]] became Bangladesh's coach in 1999.<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2006/jan/04/guardianobituaries.cricket |title=Obituary: Eddie Barlow |work=[[The Guardian]] |first=Mike |last=Selvey |date=4 January 2006 |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> In preparation for becoming a Test playing country, Bangladesh established its own first-class competition in 1999\u20142000, although the matches were not given first-class status until the 2000\u20142001 season.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/current/story/260114.html |title=A brief history of Bangladesh domestic cricket |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 September 2006 |accessdate=23 August 2011}}</ref> The lack of an established first-class structure in the country until shortly before Bangladesh played its debut Test has been cited as one of the reasons the side struggled to adapt to the longer format of the game.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ireland/content/current/story/529402.html |title=Ireland plan first-class structure |first=Andrew |last=McGlashan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=24 August 2011 |accessdate=23 August 2011}}</ref> The West Indies toured Bangladesh in October, winning both matches in the ODI series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/153897.html |title=The West Indians in Bangladesh, 1999\u20132000 |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> After suffering a stroke in April 2000, Barlow vacated the position of coach<ref name=vsEng01>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/154265.html |title=Bangladesh v England 2000\u201301 |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> and [[Sarwar Imran]] was handed the coaching job.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/18896176/when-bangladesh-strode-test-stage|title=When Bangladesh strode onto the Test stage|date=13 March 2017}}</ref> In May and June 2000, Bangladesh hosted the [[2000 Asia Cup|Asia Cup]]; Bangladesh lost all three of their matches and when playing Pakistan succumbed to what at the time was the heaviest defeat in ODIs, a margin of 233&nbsp;runs.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/154010.html |title=Pepsi Asia Cup, 1999\u20132000 |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> Bangladesh participated in the [[2000 ICC KnockOut Trophy]] in October; their only match ended in defeat by England.<ref name=vsEng01/>\n\n===First years as a Test team (2000\u20132003)===\nOn 13 November 2000, Bangladesh played their [[Indian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2000\u201301|inaugural Test match]], hosting India in Dhaka.\n{{Test match\n| date = 10\u201313 November 2000\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|BAN}}\n| team2 = {{cr-rt|IND}}\n\n| score-team1-inns1 = 400 (153.3 Overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Aminul Islam Bulbul]] 145 (380)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Sunil Joshi]] 5/142 (45.3 Overs)\n\n| score-team2-inns1 = 429 (141.3 Overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Sunil Joshi]] 92 (180)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Naimur Rahman]] 6/132 (44.3 Overs)\n\n| score-team1-inns2 = 91 (46.3 Overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Habibul Bashar]] 30 (63)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Javagal Srinath]] 3/19 (11 Overs)\n\n| score-team2-inns2 = 64/1 (15 Overs)\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[Rahul Dravid]] 41 (49)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = [[Hasibul Hossain]] 1/31 (6 Overs)\n\n| result = India won by 9 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/63898.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Bangabandhu National Stadium]], [[Dhaka]]\n| umpires = [[Steve Bucknor]] (WI) and [[David Shepherd (umpire)|David Shepherd]] (ENG)\n| motm = [[Sunil Joshi]]\n| toss = Bangladesh won the toss and elected to bat\n| rain = \n| notes =\n}}\nThe first Test run in the history of Bangladesh Cricket came from the bat of [[Mehrab Hossain (cricketer, born 1978)|Mehrab Hossain]], who also scored the first ODI hundred by an individual player for Bangladesh in 1999. Captained by [[Naimur Rahman]], Bangladesh lost by nine wickets, although ''Wisden'' noted that they \"surpassed all expectations by matching their neighbours, and at times even enjoying the upper hand\".<ref name=\"inaugural test\">{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/154208.html |first=Richard |last=Hobson |title=Bangladesh v India, 2000\u201301 |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> [[Aminul Islam Bulbul]] scored 145 in the first innings, becoming the third person to have scored a century in their team's first Test; Rahman took six wickets for 132&nbsp;runs, the second-best bowling figures in a country's maiden Test.<ref name=\"inaugural test\"/> In March 2001, former Australian Test cricketer [[Trevor Chappell]] was appointed coach.<ref name=\"Chappell and Kamal\">{{citation |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/1921128.stm |title=Bangladesh get new coach |publisher=BBC Sport |date=10 April 2002 |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> The following month Bangladesh embarked on a [[Bangladeshi cricket team in Zimbabwe in 2000\u201301|tour of Zimbabwe]] to play two Tests and three ODIs. Zimbabwe, who at the time were ranked ninth out of the ten Test teams, won all five matches.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/154233.html |title=The Bangladeshis in Zimbabwe, 2000\u201301 |first=John |last=Ward |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> Bangladesh took part in the [[2001\u201302 Asian Test Championship]], the second and final time the championship was held and the first the team had been eligible to play in. They lost both their matches by an innings. [[Mohammad Ashraful]] made his debut in the series and became the youngest player to score a Test century in his first match.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/154935.html |title=The Asian Test Championship, 2001\u201302 |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> In November, Bangladesh hosted Zimbabwe for two Tests and three ODIs. The opening Test was curtailed by bad weather and ended in a draw; after losing their first five Tests, it was the first time Bangladesh had avoided defeat. Zimbabwe won all the remaining matches. After the Test series wicketkeeper [[Khaled Mashud]] replaced Rahman as captain.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/154957.html |title=The Zimbabweans in Bangladesh, 2001\u201302 |first=Utpal |last=Shuvro |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> The following month Bangladesh journeyed to New Zealand for two Test matches. Bangladesh's batsmen struggled in unfamiliar conditions and the team slumped to two innings defeats.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/155106.html |title=The Bangladeshis in New Zealand, 2001\u201302 |first=Don |last=Cameron |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2002 Bangladesh lost two Tests and three ODIs at home against Pakistan. At this point, they had lost ten of their first eleven Tests; only South Africa had struggled as much in their introduction to Test cricket, also losing ten of their first eleven matches. Chappell blamed Bangladesh's batsmen for the loss, saying \"they commit the same mistakes again and again, and need to learn to apply themselves, to bat in sessions\".<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/155115.html |title=The Pakistanis in Bangladesh, 2001\u201302 |first=Shahid A. |last=Hashmi |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> In April, former Pakistan Test cricketer [[Mohsin Kamal]] replaced Chappell as coach.<ref name=\"Chappell and Kamal\"/> When Bangladesh [[Bangladeshi cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2002|toured Sri Lanka]] in July and August they were on the receiving end of Sri Lanka's largest margin of victory in Test cricket: an innings and 196&nbsp;runs. Bangladesh lost both Tests and all three ODIs on the tour, recording their 50th defeat in 53 ODIs. Repeated poor performances prompted people to question whether Bangladesh had been granted Test status too soon.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/155109.html |title=The Bangladeshis in Sri Lanka, 2002 |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> Two defeats against Australia and New Zealand in pool matches knocked Bangladesh out of the [[2002 ICC Champions Trophy]]. Test and ODI whitewashes followed in South Africa in October. ''Wisden'' noted that \"Time and again&nbsp;... came the mantra that [Bangladesh] would learn from the experience, that they could only improve by playing against the best, that there was genuine talent in the squad. But it wore thin.\"<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/155907.html |title=The Bangladeshis in South Africa, 2002\u201303 |first=Marcus |last=Prior |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |date=9 March 2007 |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> The final defeat set a record for most consecutive losses in ODIs (23), beating the previous record, which was also held by Bangladesh.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/284056.html |title=Records / One-Day Internationals / Team records / Most consecutive defeats |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> When the West Indies toured in November and December, Bangladesh lost both Test and two out of the three ODIs, and one ended in [[Result (cricket)|no result]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/155917.html |title=The West Indians in India and Bangladesh, 2002\u201303 |first1=Amit |last1=Varma |first2=Utpal |last2=Shuvro |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> Bangladesh hit several new lows on the third day of the first Test: their lowest innings total (87), their lowest match aggregate (226), and the biggest defeat in their 16 Tests (by an innings and 310 runs).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/155931.html|title=Bangladesh v West Indies}}</ref>\n\nSouth Africa hosted the [[2003 Cricket World Cup|2003 World Cup]] in February and March. Bangladesh lost five of their six matches (one ended in no result),<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/series/61124.html?template=fixtures |title=ICC World Cup 2002/03 / Fixtures |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> including fixtures against [[Canada national cricket team|Canada]], who hadn't played international cricket since the [[1979 Cricket World Cup|1979 World Cup]],<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/126573.html |title=Canada overwhelm Bangladesh in Durban upset |first=Samanth |last=Subramanian |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=12 February 2003 |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> and Kenya, who eventually made the semi-finals of the tournament. In the aftermath of Bangladesh's World Cup campaign, [[Khaled Mahmud|Habibul Bashar]] replaced [[Khaled Mashud]] as captain,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/214645.html |title=The South Africans in Bangladesh, 2003 |first=Brian |last=Murgatroyd |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |date=29 July 2005 |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> and Kamal was sacked as coach with [[Dav Whatmore]] taking over the role.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/124182.html |title=Bangladesh appoint Dav Whatmore as national coach |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 April 2003 |accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref> Whatmore was not able to begin the job immediately, so [[Sarwar Imran]] acted as interim coach during [[2003 TVS Cup Tri Series|TVS Cup]] and South Africa's tour of Bangladesh in April and May.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/214645.html |title=The South Africans in Bangladesh, 2003 |first=Brian |last=Murgatroyd |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |date=29 July 2005 |accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref> Bangladesh lost all four ODIs by large margins and two Tests by innings.\n\n===Under Dav Whatmore (2003\u20132007)===\nBangladesh played 7 more Tests and 11 more ODIs in 2003 against Australia, Pakistan and England, losing every single match.<ref name=\"Testlist\"/><ref name=\"ODIlist\">{{citation |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/team/25.html?class=2;template=results;type=team;view=results |title=Statsguru&nbsp;\u2013 Bangladesh&nbsp;\u2013 ODI matches&nbsp;\u2013 Team analysis |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=27 April 2012}}</ref> However, in September, Bangladesh came very close to its first Test victory, when it lost to Pakistan by only one wicket. It was just the tenth time in Test history that a team had lost by a single wicket.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/215587.html |title=Third Test match: Pakistan v Bangladesh |last=Shuvro |first=Utpal |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |date=10 August 2005 |accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref> In series against Pakistan, [[Alok Kapali]] became the first Bangladesh player to take a [[Hat-trick (cricket)|hat-trick]] in Test cricket, dismissing [[Shabbir Ahmed (cricketer)|Shabbir Ahmed]], [[Danish Kaneria]], and [[Umar Gul]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/215586.html |title=Second Test match: Pakistan v Bangladesh |last=Shuvro |first=Utpal |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |date=10 August 2005 |accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/136977.html |title=Records / Test matches / Bowling records / Hat-tricks |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref> When England toured Bangladesh October and November, Bangladesh's captain, Mahmud, was booed. Ahead of Bangladesh's [[Bangladeshi cricket team in Zimbabwe in 2003\u201304|tour of Zimbabwe]] in February and March the next year, he was dropped from the squad and batsman [[Habibul Bashar]] was granted the captaincy.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/137826.html |title=Bashar to lead Bangladesh in Zimbabwe |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=24 January 2004 |accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref> At the time, Zimbabwe were without many of their senior players. Bangladesh lost the Test series 1\u20130, and the ODI series 2\u20131.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/237446.html |title=The Bangladeshis in Zimbabwe, 2003\u201304 |last=Ward |first=John |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |date=16 February 2006 |accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref> The second Test was drawn after 3 days of no play due to heavy rains<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/137133.html |title=Bulawayo washout |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=26 February 2004 |accessdate=23 August 2011}}</ref> and brought an end to their run of 21 consecutive defeats dating back to November 2001, a world record in Test cricket.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/284055.html |title=Records / Test matches / Team records / Most consecutive defeats |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=23 August 2011}}</ref> The solitary ODI victory was Bangladesh's first international win since defeating Pakistan in the 1999 World Cup.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/237460.html |title=Third One-Day International: The Bangladeshis in Zimbabwe, 2003\u201304 |last=Ward |first=John |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |date=16 February 2006 |accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh's next matches were [[Bangladeshi cricket team in West Indies in 2004|against the West Indies]] in May and June. Bangladesh lost the ODI series 3\u20130 and the Test series 1\u20130; by securing a hard-fought draw in the first match, Bangladesh managed to avoid defeat for just the third time in 29 Tests.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/238115.html |title=The Bangladeshis in The West Indies, 2003\u201304 |first=Fazeer |last=Mohammed |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |date=20 February 2006 |accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref> Bangladesh participated [[2004 Asia Cup]] and [[2004 ICC Champions Trophy]] winning only one match against Hong Kong. In the following months, Bangladesh suffered heavy defeats in Tests and in ODIs against touring New Zealand and India. However, in December, Bangladesh defeated India in its hundredth ODI, this being only the third time that it had won against a Test playing nation.\n{{Single-innings cricket match\n| date = 26 December 2004\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|BAN}}\n| score1 = 229/9 (50 overs)\n| score2 = 214 (47.5 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|IND}}\n| runs1 = [[Aftab Ahmed (cricketer, born 1985)|Aftab Ahmed]] 67 (98)\n| wickets1 = [[Ajit Agarkar]] 2/31 (9 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Sridharan Sriram]] 57 (91)\n| wickets2 = [[Tapash Baisya]] 2/35 (10 overs)\n| result = Bangladesh won by 15 runs\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64916.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Bangabandhu National Stadium]], [[Dhaka]]\n| umpires = [[Aleem Dar]] (Pak) and [[AFM Akhtaruddin]] (Ban)\n| motm = [[Mashrafe Mortaza]] (Ban)\n| toss = Bangladesh won the toss and elected to bat\n}}\nIn January 2005, [[Zimbabwean cricket team in Bangladesh in 2004\u201305|Zimbabwe toured Bangladesh]] for two Tests and five ODIs. The touring Zimbabwe side had suffered due to player disputes which in 2004 had led to the country's temporary suspension from Test cricket. Of Zimbabwe's 16-man squad, only their captain had played more than nine Tests; Bangladesh was the more experienced team. In the first match, Bangladesh secured their maiden victory in Test cricket.<ref name=zim05>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/288794.html |title=Bangladesh v Zimbabwe, 2004\u201305 |last=Shuvro |first=Utpal |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanack |date=4 April 2007 |accessdate=14 February 2011}}</ref> Bangladesh's batsmen secured a draw in the second Test by batting out the final five session after coach Dav Whatmore had opined that \"Zimbabwe will win, unless our batsmen do something special\".<ref name=\"Haque's record\">{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/288797.html |title=Second Test: Bangladesh v Zimbabwe, 2004\u201305 |last=Shuvro |first=Utpal |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanack |date=4 April 2007 |accessdate=14 February 2011}}</ref> \n{{Test match\n| date = 6\u201310 January 2005\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|BAN}}\n| team2 = {{cr-rt|ZIM}}\n\n| score-team1-inns1 = 488 (149.3 Overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Habibul Bashar]] 94 (128)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Chris Mpofu]] 4/109 (29 Overs)\n\n| score-team2-inns1 = 312 (131.4 Overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Tatenda Taibu]] 92 (241)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Mohammad Rafique (cricketer)|Mohammad Rafique]] 5/132 (41.4 Overs)\n\n| score-team1-inns2 = 204/9 dec (51.1 Overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Habibul Bashar]] 55 (80)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Elton Chigumbura]] 5/54 (16.1 Overs)\n\n| score-team2-inns2 = 154 (64.2 Overs)\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[Hamilton Masakadza]] 56 (130)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = [[Enamul Haque jnr]] 6/45 (22.2 Overs)\n\n| result = Bangladesh won by 226 runs\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/14916/scorecard/64121/Bangladesh-vs-Zimbabwe-1st-Test-zimbabwe-tour-of-bangladesh/ Scorecard]\n| venue = [[MA Aziz Stadium]], [[Chittagong]]\n| umpires = [[Asad Rauf]] (PAK) and [[Tyron Wijewardene]] (SL)\n| motm = [[Enamul Haque jnr]] (BAN)\n| toss = Bangladesh won the toss and elected to bat\n| rain = \n| notes = First Test win ever for Bangladesh.\n}}\nIn the match \u2013 which helped secure a historic first series victory for Bangladesh \u2013 [[Enamul Haque Jr]] broke his own bowling record for best figures in an innings for Bangladesh by taking 7 wickets for 95 runs, and secured the best figures in a match for Bangladesh: 12 wickets for 200 runs<ref name=\"Haque's record\"/> and captain [[Habibul Bashar]] hit half centuries in both innings. In the ODI series that followed, [[Zimbabwe]] won the opening two contests, and Bangladesh won the final three to take the ODI series.<ref name=zim05/>\n\nAfter their maiden Test victory, Bangladesh embarked on its first tour of England in [[Bangladeshi cricket team in England in 2005|May and June 2005]]. The team faced unfamiliar conditions and the batsmen struggled against [[seam bowling]]. Bangladesh lost both matches in the Test series by an innings; the second Test was the 22nd time it had happened in 38 Tests.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/259968.html |title=England v Bangladesh 2005 |first=Andrew |last=Miller |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanack |date=19 September 2006 |accessdate=14 February 2011}}</ref> Pundits [[Mike Atherton]] and [[Richie Benaud]] criticised the team's performances and suggested Bangladesh was not yet suited to Test cricket.<ref>{{citation |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/4591115.stm |title=Bangladesh coach defends status |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 May 2005 |accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref> A triangular series with England and Australia followed. Bangladesh won just one match out of six, but their solitary victory was against an Australian side that at the time were world champions in what ''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]'' described as \"the biggest upset in one-day international history\".\n{{Single-innings cricket match\n| date = 18 June\n| time = \n| daynight = \n| team1 = {{cr-rt|AUS}}\n| score1 = 249/5 (50 overs)\n| score2 = 250/5 (49.2 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|BAN}}\n| runs1 = [[Damien Martyn]] 77 (112)\n| wickets1 = [[Tapash Baisya]] 3/69 (10 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Mohammad Ashraful]] 100 (101)\n| wickets2 = [[Jason Gillespie]] 2/41 (9.2 overs)\n| result = Bangladesh won by 5 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/211364.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Sophia Gardens (cricket ground)|Sophia Gardens]], [[Cardiff]]\n| umpires = [[Billy Bowden|BF Bowden]] (NZ) and [[David Shepherd (umpire)|DR Shepherd]] (Eng)\n| motm = [[Mohammad Ashraful]] (Ban)\n| toss = Australia won the toss and elected to bat.\n| rain = \n| notes = First odi win by Bangladesh against Australia.\n}}\nMohammad Ashraful scored his first century in that match with a score of exactly 100, which was enough to take the team to victory and then played a blistering knock of 94 off 53 balls against England the following match.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/259977.html |title=The NatWest Series 2005 |first=Julian |last=Guyer |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanack |date=19 September 2006 |accessdate=14 February 2011}}</ref> Bangladesh's next fixture was in Sri Lanka in [[Bangladeshi cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2005\u201306|September]] for two Tests and three ODIs. After the one-off victory against Australia in England, Bangladesh was a more confident team; however, Sri Lanka won all five matches by large margins. Captain Habibul Bashar lamented his side's defeat, describing it as \"the worst tour since I took over the captaincy\".<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/289099.html |title=Sri Lanka v Bangladesh, 2005\u201306 |first=Charlie |last=Austin |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanack |date=5 April 2007 |accessdate=14 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe home season of 2006 began with some optimism for Bangladesh, which registered its first win against [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]] ever in the second match of the ODI series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/290921.html|title=Bangladesh v Sri Lanka, 2005\u201306|date=17 April 2007}}</ref> However Bangladesh lost both ODI and Test series 2\u20131 and 2\u20130 respectively. At the end of March, Bangladesh played four ODIs against [[Kenya national cricket team|Kenya]], winning all. Then in April, Bangladesh came very close to beating Australia in a Test match, taking a first-innings lead of 158, and eventually losing by only three wickets.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/244298.html |title='It was a moral victory for us'&nbsp;\u2013 Bashar |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 April 2006 |accessdate=4 November 2008}}</ref> Bangladesh lost the second Test by an innings and three ODIs by huge margins. At the end of July, Bangladesh toured Zimbabwe as the ODI series as favourites but lost 3\u20132. In August, the team defeated Kenya in all three matches of a series. India hosted the [[2006 ICC Champions Trophy]] in October and November. Bangladesh failed to progress beyond the group stages, losing two of their three matches. Their only victory came against Zimbabwe.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/iccct2006/content/story/262608.html |first=S |last=Rajesh |title=Nafees stars in Bangladesh's win |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=13 October 2006 |accessdate=14 February 2011}}</ref> Bangladesh won their inaugural T20I match against Zimbabwe in front of the home crowd and subsequently went on to whitewash the same opponent in the five match ODI series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/291202.html|title=Bangladesh v Zimbabwe, 2006\u201307|date=18 April 2007}}</ref> Bangladesh capped year 2006 with two more ODI victories over Scotland. That year, [[Shahriar Nafees]] became the first Bangladeshi to score over a thousand runs (which included three centuries) in a calendar year,<ref>{{citation|url=http://ns.bdnews24.com/details.php?id=46084&cid=5 |title=Tigers scotch Scots as Mashrafe becomes year's top wicket-taker |publisher=bdnews24.com |date=15 December 2006 |accessdate=24 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707215657/http://ns.bdnews24.com/details.php?id=46084&cid=5 |archivedate=7 July 2011 }}</ref> while [[Mashrafe Mortaza]] became the leading wicket-taker in the world in ODIs staged in 2006 with 49&nbsp;wickets.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283219.html |title=One-Day Internationals: Most wickets in a calendar year |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=4 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nAhead of the World Cup Bangladesh faced Zimbabwe in four ODIs, and [[Bermuda national cricket team|Bermuda]] and Canada one each; of those matches, Bangladesh lost a single ODI to Zimbabwe.<ref name=\"ODIlist\"/> [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]], Bangladesh, [[India national cricket team|India]] and [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]] were the only teams to win both of their warm-up games. On 17 March, in their first match of the [[2007 Cricket World Cup|2007 World Cup]], hosted by the West Indies, Bangladesh secured a five-wicket win over India; the surprise result triggered late night partying in Bangladesh despite government bans on public gatherings.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wc2007/content/story/285876.html |title=Bangladesh parties after India upset |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=18 March 2007 |accessdate=24 July 2011}}</ref> In their remaining group matches Bangladesh lost to Sri Lanka and defeated Bermuda, which was enough to secure qualification for the second round while India was knocked out. Bangladesh's only victory in the Super Eights was against South Africa, losing to everyone else including [[Ireland cricket team|Ireland]],<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wc2007/engine/series/125929.html?view=pointstable |title=ICC World Cup 2006/07 / Points table |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=24 July 2011}}</ref> a team mostly made up of amateur cricketers.<ref>{{citation |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ireland/content/story/308932.html |title=Tough at the top |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |first=Andrew |last=McGlashan |date=1 September 2007 |accessdate=24 July 2011}}</ref> In April 2007, after four years as coach Whatmore chose not to extend his contract, but agreed to remain in charge until the end of May, to allow the BCB to find and appoint his successor and also to guide the side through the [[Indian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2007|two Tests and three ODIs at home against India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvind/content/story/291550.html|title=Whatmore quits as Bangladesh coach|date=20 April 2007}}</ref> After Bangladesh had helped knock India out of the tournament, the series was seen as an opportunity for India to exact revenge. India won the three match ODI series 2\u20130, one being washed out. Bangladesh had not played Test cricket since April 2006. The first Test was shortened due to rain and drawn, but India won the second by their largest margin ever (by an innings and 239 runs).<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/347035.html |title=Bangladesh v India, 2007 |first=Utpal |last=Shuvro |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |date=19 April 2008 |accessdate=14 February 2011}}</ref> In the aftermath Habibul Bashar, who had previously resigned as ODI captain, was replaced as captain by 22-year-old Mohammad Ashraful in all forms of the game. Mashrafe Mortaza was appointed vice-captain.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/296705.html |title=Ashraful named Bangladesh captain |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=2 June 2007 |accessdate=4 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Under Shaun Williams (2007)===\nBCB appointed their Under-19 coach [[Shaun Williams (cricket coach)|Shaun Williams]] as the Bangladesh's interim coach, until they find Whatmore's long term successor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/296705.html|title=Ashraful named Bangladesh captain|date=2 June 2007}}</ref> [[Mohammad Ashraful|Ashraful's]] first series in charge was a [[Bangladeshi cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2007|tour of Sri Lanka]] in June and July. Bangladesh suffered heavy defeats in each of the three Tests; losing by an innings on every occasion, and three ODIs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/series/293426.html|title=Bangladesh tour of Sri Lanka|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> In the first innings of the second Test, Bangladesh was bundled out for their lowest total (62).<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/395691.html |title=Sri Lanka v Bangladesh 2007 |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |first=Charlie |last=Austin |date=18 March 2009 |accessdate=14 February 2011}}</ref> Prior to the [[2007 ICC World Twenty20|World T20]], Bangladesh played two T20Is in Kenya. Here, they enjoyed victory over Kenya, but lost to Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/series/306979.html|title=Results \u2013 Global \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> South Africa hosted the [[2007 ICC World Twenty20]] in September. Bangladesh defeated the West Indies at the group stage to progress to the Super 8 stage of the tournament. However, it was the only match they won in the tournament, losing next four matches.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/380497.html |title=ICC World Twenty20, 2007\u201308 |first=Hugh |last=Chevallier |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |date=2 December 2008 |accessdate=14 February 2011}}</ref> During the Super 8 match against Bangladesh, Australian fast bowler [[Brett Lee]] took the first Twenty20 International (T20I) hat-trick ever achieved.\n\n===Under Jamie Siddons (2007\u20132011)===\n\nIn late October, BCB appointed [[Jamie Siddons]], an Australian cricketer, as their head coach.<ref>{{citation |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/other_international/bangladesh/7066384.stm |title=Siddons signs as Bangladesh coach |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 October 2007 |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> Towards the end of 2007, Bangladesh toured New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/series/300412.html|title=Bangladesh tour of New Zealand|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> They were soundly beaten 3\u20130 in the one-dayers. Bangladesh started the new year with the Test leg of the tour. These matches were also one-sided, where Bangladesh lost the series 2\u20130.\n\nA touring South Africa clean swept Bangladesh across formats in February\u2013March 2008. The tour included two Tests and three ODIs. However, in the 1st Test, Bangladesh secured a first innings lead of 22 runs after restricting South Africa for 170.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvrsa/content/series/323940.html|title=South Africa tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Bangladesh then defeated non-Test-playing Ireland 3\u20130 in an ODI series at home in the same month, ending a run of 14 losses.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvireland/content/series/335630.html|title=Ireland tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Pakistan hosted Bangladesh for 5 ODIs and a T20I in April. It was a miserable tour for Bangladesh where they lost all games<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakvbdesh/content/series/343065.html|title=Bangladesh tour of Pakistan|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh lost both first-round games against Pakistan and India at a triangular ODI tournament held in Bangladesh in June.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/kitplycup/engine/series/345463.html?view=pointstable|title=Points Table \u2013 Kitply Cup 2008 \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2008 Asia Cup]] held in Pakistan, Bangladesh won their first group stage game against associate UAE. Even though they lost to Sri Lanka in the next group stage match, Bangladesh reached the super four stage, before losing the next three games against India, Sri Lanka and Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/asiacup/engine/series/298014.html?view=pointstable|title=Points Table \u2013 Asia Cup \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nThey were later got whitewashed 0\u20133 in the ODIs during their tour to Australia in August\u2013September.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ausvbdesh/content/series/336196.html|title=Bangladesh tour of Australia|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nIn October, [[New Zealand cricket team in Bangladesh in 2008\u201309|New Zealand toured Bangladesh]] for three ODIs and two Tests. Shortly before the tour, fourteen Bangladesh players left to play in the [[Indian Cricket League]] and were subsequently banned for ten years. Six of the players were centrally contracted, including former captain [[Habibul Bashar]]. With a less experienced team than usual and a poor record against New Zealand, Bangladesh was expected to lose heavily. After winning the opening ODI (their first ODI victory ever over New Zealand), Bangladesh went on to lose series 2\u20131.<ref name=nz08>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/431964.html |title=Bangladesh v New Zealand 2008\u201309 |first=Utpal |last=Shuvro |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |date=29 October 2009 |accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref> New Zealand won the first Test by three wickets in what their coach, [[John Bracewell]], described as \"one of the great character wins\".<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/431973.html |title=First Test: Bangladesh v New Zealand 2008\u201309 |first=Utpal |last=Shuvro |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |date=29 October 2009 |accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref> The second Test ended up in a rain curtailed draw, sealing the series victory for New Zealand (1\u20130). But in the process [[Shakib Al Hasan]] emerged as an all-rounder. Having previously been selected primarily as a batsman, he went on to take the best bowling figures in an innings for a Bangladesh player, 7 wickets for 36 runs, beating the record set by Enamul Haque Jr three years earlier.\n\nIn November, Bangladesh toured South Africa. They lost all their matches to South Africa, including the only T20I match, two of the three ODIs (the third being washed out due to rain) and both Tests by innings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/rsavbdesh/content/series/350336.html|title=Bangladesh tour of South Africa|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nIn December, however, Bangladesh bounced back from the previous lackluster performances by threatening to win the first Test match against Sri Lanka at home by chasing down the highest fourth innings total of 513. Though they fell 107 runs short, their performances were praised.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvsl/content/story/384811.html|title=Brave Bangladesh fall 107 short|date=31 December 2008}}</ref> But in the second test match of this home series in January, Bangladesh succumbed to a 465 runs defeat, conceding the series 2\u20130 to Sri Lanka.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvsl/content/series/378736.html|title=Sri Lanka tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Then Zimbabwe joined the hosts and the Lankan team for a tri-series ODI tournament, which proved to be more evenly matched than was expected. In the first match, Zimbabwe defeated Bangladesh by an excellent performance, but then was defeated by Sri Lanka by a huge margin, leaving Bangladesh needing to win with a bonus point against the Lankans in the last group match to go through to the finals to join the Lankans. In a reduced match due to rain interruptions Bangladesh recorded their second ODI win over Sri Lanka to reach the finals. However at the Finals, they were beaten by the Lankans who claimed the Series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/tri-bdesh/content/story/386587.html|title=Murali cameo clinches humdinger|date=16 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nLater in the same month the three match ODI series against Zimbabwe at home was won by Bangladesh 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvzim/content/series/378739.html|title=Zimbabwe tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2009 ICC World Twenty20]] held in England, Bangladesh crashed out of the tournament at the group stage after losing both games against India and associate Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wt202009/engine/series/335113.html?view=pointstable|title=Points Table \u2013 ICC World Twenty20 2009 \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nAftermath of the losses at the global event, the selectors appointed Mashrafe Mortaza as the new captain of the team for the [[Bangladeshi cricket team in West Indies in 2009|tour to the West Indies]] so that Ashraful could focus on his batting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/current/story/410237.html|title=Mortaza named Bangladesh captain|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=23 June 2009 |accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref> The two Test series was played amidst controversy when a pay dispute between the West Indian players and the West Indies Cricket Board led a number of West Indian players boycotting the series, which forced the West Indies to select a number of inexperienced players as replacements.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/story/413458.html|title=The origins of the issue|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=9 July 2009 |accessdate=21 July 2009}}</ref> Bangladesh went on to win both of the Tests, winning the first Test by 95 runs<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.cricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/engine/current/match/401071.html|title=Scorecard: West Indies v Bangladesh, 1st Test, 9\u201313 July 2009|work=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=21 July 2009}}</ref> and the second by four wickets.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/engine/current/match/401072.html|title=Scorecard: West Indies v Bangladesh, 2nd Test, 17\u201320 July 2009|work=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=21 July 2009}}</ref> In the process they achieved their first overseas Test series victory.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/current/story/415358.html|title=Raqibul and Shakib inspire first overseas series win|last=Veera|first=Sriram|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 July 2009 |accessdate=21 July 2009}}</ref>\nIn the ODI series which followed, Bangladesh secured their first ODI win against the West Indies at the 14th attempt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nation.ittefaq.com/issues/2009/07/28/news0192.htm |title=Sports Minister congratulates Bangladesh cricket team|publisher=The New Nation|accessdate=27 July 2009}}</ref> Bangladesh won the series 3\u20130,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/story/417154.html |title=Bangladesh complete 3\u20130 sweep |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |first=Sriram |last=Veera |date=31 July 2009 |accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref> but lost the only Twenty20 match.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/story/417469.html |title=West Indies earn consolation win |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |first=Sriram |last=Veera |date=2 August 2009 |accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh emerged victorious 4\u20131<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/zimvbdesh2009/content/series/410334.html|title=Bangladesh tour of Zimbabwe|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and 4\u20131<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvzim09/content/series/422622.html|title=Zimbabwe tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> in back to back five match ODI series against Zimbabwe away (in August) and home (in October\u2013November).\n\nIn November, Shakib was named ''[[The Wisden Cricketer]]'s'' \"Test Player of the Year\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/cricket/shakib-al-hasan-wins-wisden-cricketer-magazines-test-player-of-the-year-award/news-story/f4edc1244a425d229408d7746734445b|title=Al Hasan named Wisden's top Test player|date=8 October 2009}}</ref>\n[[File:Shakib al hasan 2.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Shakib Al Hasan]] captained Bangladesh during their historic Test series win against West Indies in 2009.]]\n\nIn January 2010, Bangladesh hosted a tri-series ODI tournament with India and Sri Lanka. They failed to win a match (in 4 matches) and went out of the tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/table/series/8631/season/2010/tri-nation-tournament-in-bangladesh|title=Tri-Nation Tournament in Bangladesh Table \u2013 2010|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> That was followed by a two-match Test series against India at home, which Bangladesh lost 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvind2010/content/series/434243.html|title=India tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nDuring full away tour in February 2010 against New Zealand, Bangladesh lost all matches (only T20I, three ODIs and only Test).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/nzvbdesh2010/content/series/423769.html|title=Bangladesh tour of New Zealand|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nIn February\u2013March 2010, [[England Cricket Team|England]] visited Bangladesh to play [[English cricket team in Bangladesh in 2009\u201310|three ODIs and two Test matches]]. Bangladesh lost all their ODIs and Tests in the series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshveng2010/content/series/426373.html|title=England tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nIn May, Bangladesh took part in the [[2010 World Twenty20]]. They lost all their matches at group stage (against Pakistan and Australia) and failed to progress to the Super Eights stage.\n\nIn May and June, Bangladesh played two Test matches [[Bangladeshi cricket team in England in 2010|against England away]], losing both, although [[Tamim Iqbal]] scored two centuries in the series.<ref name=\"espncricinfo.com1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-bangladesh-2010/content/series/426339.html|title=Bangladesh tour of England, Ireland and Scotland|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nBetween the Tests and ODIs against England, Bangladesh took part in the [[2010 Asia Cup]] during June, but lost all their matches vs India, Sri Lanka and Pakistan.\n\nIn the ODI series, England comfortably won the first match. However, in the second match at Bristol, Bangladesh beat England for the first time in international cricket (England were the only Test playing nation yet to be beaten by Bangladesh), bowling England out in the final over to win by five runs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://m.cricinfo.com/s/2497/MatchCenter?countryId=25&country=bangladesh&matchId=426404&tournamentName=NatWest%20Series%20%5BBangladesh%20in%20England%5D&matchTitle=2nd%20ODI&team1=England&team2=Bangladesh&startDate=Jul%2010%2C%202010&result=true|title=Live cricket scores, commentary, match coverage \u2013 Cricket news, statistics \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|work=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref>\n{{Single-innings cricket match\n | date = 10 July 2010\n | team1 = {{cr-rt|BAN}}\n | score1 = 236/7 (50 overs)\n | score2 = 231 (49.3 overs)\n | team2 = {{cr|ENG}}\n | runs1 = [[Imrul Kayes]] 76 (111)\n | wickets1 = [[Ajmal Shahzad]] 3/41 (10 overs)\n | runs2 = [[Jonathan Trott]] 94 (130)\n | wickets2 = [[Shafiul Islam]] 2/38 (9.3 overs)\n | result = Bangladesh won by 5 runs\n | report = [http://www.cricinfo.com/england-v-bangladesh-2010/engine/match/426404.html Scorecard]\n | venue = [[County Cricket Ground, Bristol|County Ground]], Bristol\n | umpires = [[Asad Rauf]] (Pak) and [[Richard Illingworth]] (Eng)\n | motm = [[Mashrafe Mortaza]] (Ban)\n | toss = England won the toss and elected to field.\n}}\nHowever England won the third ODI at Birmingham and sealed the series 2\u20131.<ref name=\"espncricinfo.com1\"/> Bangladesh extended this tour in Europe to play 2 match ODIs series against Ireland. The series was shared (1\u20131). The one-off ODI against Scotland was abandoned due to heavy rains. Later Netherlands won the last one-off ODI of the tour.<ref name=\"espncricinfo.com1\"/>\n\nIn October [[New Zealand cricket team in Bangladesh in 2010\u201311|New Zealand went to Bangladesh]] for five ODIs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-new-zealand-2010/content/series/476044.html|title=New Zealand tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Mortaza suffered an injury in the first match and Shakib took over as captain. Under his leadership Bangladesh won the series 4\u20130 (2nd ODI was abandoned due to rain), securing their first series victory against a full strength ICC Full Member nation.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-new-zealand-2010/content/story/482305.html |title=Bangladesh reap rewards of hard work |first=Mohammad |last=Isam |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=18 October 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-new-zealand-2010/content/story/481617.html |title=All-round Shakib inspires Bangladesh to historic win |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |first=Andrew |last=Fernando |date=14 October 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-new-zealand-2010/content/story/480285.html |title=Mortaza ruled out due to injury |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=6 October 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nAlthough unable to play against New Zealand due to injury, while the series was in progress [[Tamim Iqbal]] was named ''The Wisden Cricketer's'' \"Test Player of the Year\".<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/481789.html |title=Tamim named Wisden Cricketer Test Player of the Year |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 October 2010 |accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn December Bangladesh hosted Zimbabwe for [[Zimbabwean cricket team in Bangladesh in 2010\u201311|five ODIs]]. After losing the opening match,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-zimbabwe-2010/content/story/490108.html |title='I was not prepared for captaincy'&nbsp;\u2013 Shakib Al Hasan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=2 December 2010 |accessdate=2 December 2010}}</ref> Bangladesh went on to win the next three complete matches, with 4th ODI called off due to rain, to beat Zimbabwe 3\u20131.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-zimbabwe-2010/content/current/story/491571.html |title=Shakib praises Bangladesh recovery |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=12 December 2010 |accessdate=12 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn February and March 2011, Bangladesh co-hosted the [[2011 Cricket World Cup|World Cup]] with India and Sri Lanka. Bangladesh lost the tournament opener against India, before the win against Ireland. The next match was won by West Indies after dismissing Bangladesh for 58 runs, the team's lowest score in ODIs and a record low for a Full Member at the World Cup.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/504517.html |title='Team devastated by performance'&nbsp;\u2013 Siddons |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |first=Sidharth |last=Monga |date=6 March 2011 |accessdate=6 March 2011}}</ref> The West Indies and Bangladesh team buses were stoned as they left the ground,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/504279.html |title=West Indies team bus stoned in Dhaka |first=Sidharth |last=Monga |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=4 March 2011 |accessdate=6 March 2011}}</ref> and so was Shakib's house.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/504533.html |title=Shakib, Siddons hit back at criticism from former players |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |first=Sidharth |last=Monga |date=6 March 2011 |accessdate=6 March 2011}}</ref> Bangladesh later defeated England, and the Netherlands, making their final match of the group stage a must-win contest. Against South Africa, Bangladesh succumbed to their second-largest defeat in ODIs and became the first Full Member team to be bowled out for under 100 twice in World Cups, thereby failing to progress to the knockout stage of the tournament.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/506964.html |title=Abject Bangladesh surrender meekly |first=Abhishek |last=Purohit |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=19 March 2011 |accessdate=20 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nThen Australia complete a 3\u20130 sweep in ODIs against Bangladesh when they visited the country in April.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-australia-2011/content/series/503357.html|title=Australia tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nMiddle of the Australian visit, BCB confirmed that Siddons unlikely to win a contract extension from the moment his team failed to meet lofty home expectations during the 2011 World Cup.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/510797.html |title=Siddons' Bangladesh tenure ends |first=Daniel |last=Brettig |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=12 April 2011 |accessdate=20 June 2011}}</ref> Under his mentorship, Bangladesh won 2 Tests (in 19), 31 ODIs (in 84). They did not win any T20Is (in 8) during this period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=11;filter=advanced;orderby=start;spanmax1=01+jul+2011;spanmin1=31+oct+2007;spanval1=span;team=25;template=results;type=team|title=Team records \u2013 Combined Test, ODI and T20I records \u2013 Cricinfo Statsguru \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> First overseas Test series victory, first Test match and series victories over West Indies, first ODI wins against New Zealand, West Indies and England, clean sweeps in ODIs against West Indies (away) and New Zealand (home), reaching the final of a triangular tournament where all participants are ICC full members, consistent wins in bilateral ODI series against Zimbabwe (4) were the highlights for Siddons as the Bangladesh head coach. During his three-and-a-half-year tenure as coach Siddons introduced a full coaching staff for the first time, including coaches for bowling, strength and conditioning, and fielding. Under Siddons Bangladesh's reliance on spin bowlers continued, partly because pitches in the country encourage spin bowlers, and frequently only two seam bowlers were used in a match. Siddons was credited with helping the team improve mentally.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/519381.html |title=Lessons from Siddons |first=Abu |last=Choudhury |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=19 June 2011 |accessdate=20 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Under Stuart Law (2011\u20132012) ===\nA lengthy hunt for a head coach, followed Siddons' exit encountering the names of [[Vincent Barnes]] and [[Stuart Law]] as possible appointees.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/517998.html |title=Vincent Barnes declines Bangladesh coaching job |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=6 June 2011 |accessdate=29 June 2011}}</ref> Law, who at the time was the interim head coach of [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]] following [[Trevor Bayliss]]' departure, was named Bangladesh's new head coach starting from 1 July 2011.<ref name=\"new Law\">{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/srilanka/content/story/520898.html |title=Law to take over as Bangladesh coach |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=27 June 2011 |accessdate=29 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh toured Zimbabwe in August 2011 for a one-off Test and five ODIs.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/zimbabwe-v-bangladesh-2011/content/current/story/523380.html |title=Uncapped Nasir, Shuvagoto in squad for Zimbabwe |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=15 July 2011 |accessdate=15 July 2011}}</ref> The Test marked Zimbabwe's return to the longest-format of the game, after a self-imposed withdrawal in January 2006 as the sport in the country was in a state of disarray. Bangladesh lost the match by 130&nbsp;runs.<ref>{{citation |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/14449989.stm |title=Zimbabwe beat Bangladesh on return to Test cricket |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 August 2011 |accessdate=9 August 2011}}</ref> Though they were expected to do well with the Test and the ODIs, Bangladesh lost the subsequent one-day series 3\u20132. In the aftermath of the series, captain [[Shakib Al Hasan]] and vice captain [[Tamim Iqbal]] were sacked from their leadership roles, with a BCB representative citing their poor leadership.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/current/story/531274.html |title=Shakib and Tamim stripped of leadership roles |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=5 September 2011 |accessdate=5 September 2011}}</ref> Later that month, wicket-keeper [[Mushfiqur Rahim]] was named captain, with all-rounder [[Mahmudullah]] as his deputy.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/533124.html |title=Mushfiqur Rahim named Bangladesh captain |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 September 2011 |accessdate=20 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh' struggles at international level have been epitomised by the ineffectiveness of their fast bowlers. Between January 2010 and August 2011, they took 37&nbsp;wickets in 8&nbsp;Tests at an average of 67.67, the worst out of the nine teams playing regular Test cricket in this period.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/527068.html |title=England's pace pack, and Johnson's Asia heroics |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=12 August 2011 |accessdate=9 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nThough Bangladesh won Rahim's first match in charge, the only T20I against West Indies at home in October, the team lost the subsequent ODI series 2\u20131 and the two-match Test series 1\u20130.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-west-indies-2011/engine/series/531420.html |title=West Indies tour of Bangladesh 2011/12 / Results |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=17 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nPakistan [[Pakistani cricket team in Bangladesh in 2011\u201312|toured in December]], and during the first of three ODIs Bangladesh were dismissed for their 13th score of less than 100 in the format, overtaking Zimbabwe's record of 12&nbsp;times.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-pakistan-2011/content/current/story/543170.html |title=Afridi's five leads rout of Bangladesh |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |first=George |last=Binoy |date=1 December 2011 |accessdate=1 December 2011}}</ref> Bangladesh got whitewashed comprehensively across formats, 0\u20131 (T20I), 0\u20133 (ODIs) and 0\u20132 (Tests).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-pakistan-2011/content/series/538064.html|title=Pakistan tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nIn March Bangladesh hosted in the [[2012 Asia Cup]] featuring India, Pakistan, and Sri Lanka. Bangladesh entered the tournament with just two wins from 29 Asia Cup matches.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/asia-cup-2012/content/story/558198.html |title=Bangladesh's chance for unprecedented glory |first=Abhishek |last=Purohit |publisher=Cricinfon |date=21 March 2012 |accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref> Victories against India and Sri Lanka saw Bangladesh face Pakistan in the final, only the second time the team had reached the final of a multi-national competition.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/asia-cup-2012/content/story/558027.html |title=Team effort takes Bangladesh to historic final |first=Kanishkaa |last=Balachandran |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 March 2012 |accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref> Though Pakistan won the final by two runs, Bangladesh had exceeded expectations.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/asia-cup-2012/content/story/558267.html |title=Pakistan prevail over gutsy Bangladesh |first=Abhishek |last=Purohit |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=22 March 2012 |accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref> During the tournament, Tamim Iqbal became the first Bangladeshi player to score four consecutive fifties in ODIs. Shakib Al Hasan was named man of the series after contributing with both the bat and the ball, making 237 runs and taking 6 wickets respectively.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/asia-cup-2012/content/story/558358.html |title=Middle-over batting costs Bangladesh  |first=Madhusudhan |last=Ramakrishnan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=22 March 2012 |accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe following month Law announced he would be stepping down as coach in June when his contract was due to expire for personal reasons.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/561426.html |title=Stuart Law quits as Bangladesh coach |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=16 April 2012 |accessdate=18 April 2012}}</ref> Bangladesh had not won any Tests (in 5) under Law. Further they only won 5 ODIs (in 15) and 1 T20I (in 2) during this period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=11;filter=advanced;orderby=start;spanmax1=30+jun+2012;spanmin1=01+jul+2011;spanval1=span;team=25;template=results;type=team|title=Team records \u2013 Combined Test, ODI and T20I records \u2013 Cricinfo Statsguru \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> Reaching the finals of [[Asia Cup 2012]] was the pinnacle of Law's tenure as Bangladesh coach.\n\n=== Under Richard Pybus (2012) ===\nIn May 2012 Bangladesh have appointed England born [[Richard Pybus]] as their new head coach for two-years, replacing [[Stuart Law]] who stepped down from the post in April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/may/30/richard-prybus-bangladesh-cricket-coach|title=Bangladesh appoint Richard Pybus as new head coach on two-year deal |date=30 May 2012 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nDuring Bangladesh tour of Ireland and Netherlands in July, they clean swept the three match T20I series against Ireland, lost a T20I against Scotland and shared the two match T20I series against Netherlands 1\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ireland-nl-v-bangladesh-2012/content/series/567068.html|title=Bangladesh tour of Ireland and Netherlands|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh crashed out of the [[2012 ICC World Twenty20]] by losing to New Zealand and Pakistan in the first round.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2012/engine/series/531597.html?view=pointstable|title=Points Table \u2013 ICC World Twenty20 2012 \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nAfter only four months at the helm, Pybus notified the BCB of his unwillingness to continue due to issues with his contract and interference from administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/587679.html|title=Pybus to quit as Bangladesh coach|date=23 October 2012}}</ref> Under him Bangladesh won 4 T20Is (in 8).\n\n=== Under Shane Jurgensen (2012\u20132014) ===\nThe team's bowling coach and Australian [[Shane Jurgensen]] was appointed as the interim Bangladesh coach for the series against West Indies at home in November\u2013December 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/587982.html|title=Jurgensen is interim Bangladesh coach|date=24 October 2012}}</ref> The home side lost the two Tests, but won the ODI series 3\u20132, before losing the only T20I.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-west-indies-2012/content/series/586566.html|title=West Indies tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, BCB announced that Jurgensen will continue as Bangladesh's head coach for the rest of the year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/604284.html|title=Shane Jurgensen becomes full-time Bangladesh coach \u2013 Cricket \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=9 February 2013 |accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh toured Sri Lanka in March 2013 for a full series. In the 1st Test at Galle [[Mushfiqur Rahim]] scored the first double century for Bangladesh in test cricket,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/602472.html|title=1st Test: Sri Lanka v Bangladesh at Galle, Mar 8\u201312, 2013 \u2013 Cricket Scorecard \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|work=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref> and [[Mohammad Ashraful]] chipped in with a handy 190. They were able to draw the 1st Test against Sri Lanka, the first time ever against the island nation. Sri Lanka won the 2nd Test by 7 wickets and the two match test series 1\u20130. The three match ODI series was shared 1\u20131 since the 2nd ODI being washed out. Bangladesh lost the only T20I too.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/sri-lanka-v-bangladesh-2013/content/series/602463.html|title=Bangladesh tour of Sri Lanka|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nThen they toured Zimbabwe from April\u2013May. Bangladesh lost the 1st Test by 335 runs, which marked the Zimbabwe's biggest win. Later they won the 2nd Test by 173 runs to share the series with Zimbabwe (1\u20131). Bangladesh lost the ODI series (1\u20132) before sharing the T20I series (1\u20131).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/zimbabwe-v-bangladesh-2013/content/series/623566.html|title=Bangladesh tour of Zimbabwe|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nLater in October\u2013November 2013 Bangladesh achieved a new feat sharing the two match test series (0\u20130) on home soil against New Zealand, the first against the country. This was followed by 3\u20130 series whitewash win for Bangladesh in ODIs, before losing the only T20I.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-new-zealand-2013-14/content/series/668933.html|title=New Zealand tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nSri Lanka toured Bangladesh for full series from January\u2013February 2014. Bangladesh slip to their fourth-heaviest defeat in their Test history after losing the 1st Test by an innings and 248 runs. The 2nd test was a high scoring draw and Bangladesh lost the series (0\u20131).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/series/690341.html|title=Sri Lanka in Bangladesh Test Series|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Later they got whitewashed in the T20I (0\u20132)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/series/690343.html|title=Sri Lanka in Bangladesh T20I Series|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and the ODI (0\u20133)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/series/690345.html|title=Sri Lanka in Bangladesh ODI Series|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> series.\n\nThat was followed up by a series of defeats (0\u20134) against Asian Cricketing nations (India, Afghanistan, Pakistan, Sri Lanka) at the league stage of [[2014 Asia Cup]] conducted on their home soil and Bangladesh finished at the bottom of the table.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/asia-cup-2014/engine/series/671665.html?view=pointstable|title=Points Table \u2013 Asia Cup \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Associate Afghanistan's win against Bangladesh was their first ODI victory against a Test-playing nation.\n\nBangladesh ended their 11 match win-less run in 2014 defeating two associates (Afghanistan and Nepal) in consecutive T20Is at the [[2014 ICC World Twenty20]] Group stage. Their loss to another associate, Hong Kong, did not prevent them reaching the Super 10 stage. However at the Super 10 stage, Bangladesh lost all (0\u20134) their matches against West Indies, India, Pakistan and Australia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/world-t20/engine/series/628368.html?view=pointstable|title=Points Table \u2013 World T20 \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nThe coach resigned from his position less than a month after the World T20, where the team won just two out of seven matches. Under Jurgensen, Bangladesh won 1 Test (in 10), 8 ODIs (in 21) and 3 T20Is (in 14). Highlights of his tenure were the Test win after 4 years (against Zimbabwe), shared two-test series against New Zealand at home, 3\u20130 ODI clean sweep against New Zealand at home and securing 2 draws in Tests against Sri Lanka (away and home).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/740185.html|title=Shane Jurgensen resigns as Bangladesh coach \u2013 Cricket \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=28 April 2014 |accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Under Chandika Hathurusingha (2014\u20132017) ===\n[[File:Mushfiqur_Rahim_2009_(cropped).jpg|thumb|[[Mushfiqur Rahim]] captained Bangladesh in their historic 100th test win over Sri Lanka and their first test win against England and Australia]]\n\nThe BCB appointed [[Chandika Hathurusingha]], a former Sri Lanka batsman, as Bangladesh's head coach for a two-year period.<ref name=\"espncricinfo.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/current/story/745747.html|title=Hathurusingha named Bangladesh coach|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=19 May 2014 |accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe first series under the new coach was against India at home. Bangladesh lost the first & second ODI comprehensively and the 3rd was washed out and lost the series 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-india-2014/content/series/743887.html|title=India tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh toured West Indies for a full series in August.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-bangladesh-2014/content/series/730263.html|title=Bangladesh tour of West Indies|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> West Indies beat Bangladesh 3\u20130 in the ODI series extending Bangladesh's win-less ODI run for 13 matches. In the 2nd ODI Bangladesh was bundled out for 70 which is the 3rd lowest total for Bangladesh. Bangladesh lost the match by 177 Runs. Only the T20I match was abandoned. Further, West Indies white-washed Bangladesh in the Test series 2\u20130, defeating Bangladesh by 10 wickets in the 1st Test and by 296 runs in the 2nd Test respectively.\n\nBangladesh finally emerged victorious during the [[Zimbabwean cricket team in Bangladesh in 2014\u201315|Zimbabwe tour in Bangladesh]] whitewashing the visitors 3\u20130 during the Test series. Bangladesh claimed No. 9 ranking with the series victory pushing Zimbabwe to No. 10. In the ODI series, Bangladesh whitewashed Zimbabwe 5\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-zimbabwe-2014-15/content/series/760771.html|title=Zimbabwe tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nAt the turn of the new year, Bangladeshi all-rounder [[Shakib Al Hasan]] emerged as the number one all-rounder in all formats of the game. This was the first time that any player ever achieved such a feat, after the ICC introduced ranking system.<ref name=\"news.com.au\">{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/cricket/shakib-al-hasan-just-may-be-the-worlds-best-cricketer/story-fndpt0dy-1227184515219|title=Shakib Al Hasan tops ICC all-rounder rankings in all three formats|date=14 January 2015|work=NewsComAu|accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring the group stage of the [[2015 Cricket World Cup]], Bangladesh defeated Afghanistan in their first game,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8039/scorecard/656411/Afghanistan-vs-Bangladesh-7th-Match,-Pool-A-world-cup/|title=7th match, Pool A (D/N), ICC Cricket World Cup at Canberra, Feb 18 2015 \u2013 Match Summary|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and their next match against Australia was Washed Out.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8039/scorecard/656419/Australia-vs-Bangladesh-11th-Match,-Pool-A-world-cup/|title=11th Match, Pool A (D/N), ICC Cricket World Cup at Brisbane, Feb 21 2015 \u2013 Match Summary|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> They lost their next game to Sri Lanka by 92 runs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8039/scorecard/656433/Bangladesh-vs-Sri-Lanka-18th-Match,-Pool-A-world-cup/|title=18th Match, Pool A (D/N), ICC Cricket World Cup at Melbourne, Feb 26 2015 \u2013 Match Summary|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Following that, they achieved their highest successful run-chase in an ODI, when they chased down Scotland's 318,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8039/scorecard/656451/Bangladesh-vs-Scotland-27th-Match,-Pool-A-world-cup/|title=27th Match, Pool A, ICC Cricket World Cup at Nelson, Mar 5 2015 \u2013 Match Summary|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and later qualified for the second quarterfinal in the 2015 world cup, by defeating England.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8039/scorecard/656463/Bangladesh-vs-England-33rd-Match,-Pool-A-world-cup/|title=33rd Match, Pool A (D/N), ICC Cricket World Cup at Adelaide, Mar 9 2015 \u2013 Match Summary|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> At the second quarter-final, India comprehensively defeated Bangladesh by 109 runs, knocking them out of the 2015 World Cup.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8039/scorecard/656485/Bangladesh-vs-India-2nd-Quarter-Final-world-cup/|title=2nd quarter-Final (D/N), ICC Cricket World Cup at Melbourne, Mar 19 2015 \u2013 Match Summary|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> After a successful world cup campaign, reaching the quarter final for the first time, the whole team was given a grand reception at the Airport on 22 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sport/cricket/world-cup/rousing-welcome-for-bangladesh-wc-team/article7021039.ece|title=Rousing welcome for Bangladesh WC team|first=Haroon|last=Habib|date=22 March 2015|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref>\n{{Single-innings cricket match\n| date = {{anchor|match33}} 9 March\n| time = 14:00 ({{tooltip|ACDT|Australian Central Daylight Time (UTC+10:30)}})\n| daynight = yes\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|BAN}}\n| team2 = {{cr|ENG}}\n| score1 = 275/7 (50 overs)\n| score2 = 260 (48.3 overs)\n| runs1 = [[Mahmudullah Riyad]] 103 (138)\n| wickets1 = [[James Anderson (cricketer)|James Anderson]] 2/45 (10 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Jos Buttler]] 65 (52)\n| wickets2 = [[Rubel Hossain]] 4/53 (9.3 overs)\n| result = Bangladesh won by 15 runs \n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/656463.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Adelaide Oval]], [[Adelaide]]\n| umpires = [[Billy Bowden]] (NZ) and [[Paul Reiffel]] (Aus)\n| motm = [[Mahmudullah Riyad]] (Ban)\n| toss = England won the toss and elected to field.\n| rain = \n| notes = [[Mahmudullah Riyad]] became the first player to score a century for Bangladesh in a World Cup match.<ref name=\"EngBang\">{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-cricket-world-cup-2015/content/story/846263.html|title=Mahmudullah ton lifts Bangladesh to 275|work=ESPNcricinfo|date=9 March 2015|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref>\n*''[[Mahmudullah Riyad]] and [[Mushfiqur Rahim]]'s partnership of 141 was the highest partnership for any wicket for Bangladesh in a World Cup match.<ref name=\"ESPN Stats\">{{cite news|url= http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-cricket-world-cup-2015/content/story/846719.html|title=Records tumble for Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo|date=9 March 2015|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> It was also Bangladesh's highest ODI partnership against England.<ref>Cricinfo \u2013 Bangladesh's Highest Partnerships by Runs http://stats.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/engine/records/fow/highest_partnerships_for_any_wicket.html?class=2;id=25;type=team</ref>\n*''This was also Bangladesh's highest score in an ODI against England.<ref name=\"EngBang\" />\n*''Bangladesh and Sri Lanka qualified for the quarter-finals as a result of this match.<ref>{{cite news|title=2015 Cricket World Cup pools and venues revealed|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/cricket/cricket-world-cup-pools-and-venues-revealed/story-fni2usfi-1226688015038|accessdate=3 March 2014|newspaper=Herald Sun|date=30 July 2013}}</ref> This was only the second time that Bangladesh had progressed past the World Cup Group stages and it is their first appearance in a knockout stage of a World Cup.<ref name=\"EngOut\"/>\n*''England was eliminated from the World Cup as a result of this match.<ref name=\"EngOut\">{{cite news|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/31792930|title= Cricket World Cup 2015: England knocked out by Bangladesh|work=BBC Sport|date=9 March 2015|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref>\n*''Bangladesh captain [[Mashrafe Mortaza]] was fined 40% of his match fee for a slow over rate. The other Bangladesh players were fined 20% of their match fee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.ndtv.com/icc-cricket-world-cup-2015/news/238766-world-cup-2015-bangladesh-fined-for-slow-over-rate-in-win-over-england|title=World Cup 2015: Bangladesh Fined for Slow Over-Rate in Win Over England|publisher=NDTV|date=9 March 2015|accessdate=2 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402220117/http://sports.ndtv.com/icc-cricket-world-cup-2015/news/238766-world-cup-2015-bangladesh-fined-for-slow-over-rate-in-win-over-england|archive-date=2 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\nIn April\u2013May 2015 [[Pakistani cricket team in Bangladesh in 2014\u201315|Pakistan]] was in Bangladesh for a full series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-pakistan-2015/content/series/856311.html|title=Pakistan tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Bangladesh won the ODI series 3\u20130 recording their first series victory over Pakistanis. The only T20I was also won by Bangladesh. However Pakistan claimed the Test series victory (1\u20130), by drawing the first test and winning the second test by 328 runs.\n\nA full strength Indian team arrived in Bangladesh in June 2015, for an one-off Test and 3 ODIs, where the Indians were expected to win comfortably. During the Test, the Indian team was too strong for Bangladesh where they were enforced to follow on. But the heavy rain interruptions denied a decisive result (only 184.2 overs were played). However excellent performances by the batsmen and ODI debutant bowler [[Mustafizur Rahman]] had the tables turned over as Bangladesh convincingly won the first two ODIs and for the first time, won a bilateral series [[Indian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2015|against India]] by a margin of 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-india-2015/content/series/870723.html|title=India tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nDuring July 2015 South Africa visited Bangladesh for 2 T20Is, 3 ODIs and 2 Tests.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-south-africa-2015/content/series/817095.html|title=South Africa tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> South Africa whitewashed Bangladesh in the T20I series (2\u20130) and took the lead of ODI series winning the first match. However Bangladesh came back strongly and completely dominated South Africa in the following two matches, showing excellent performance in all three departments where none of the team in any match could reach 200 runs in an innings in the whole ODI series, to win the series by a margin of 2\u20131, which marked the first series win ever against South Africa.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-south-africa-2015/content/story/898901.html | title=Bangladesh seal series with nine-wicket win | work=ESPNcricinfo | accessdate=7 March 2016| date=15 July 2015 }}</ref> Two match test series was shared (0\u20130) after heavy monsoon rains curtailed both games (played 221<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/11365/report/817213/Bangladesh-vs-South-Africa-1st-Test-south-africa-tour-of-bangladesh|title=1st Test, South Africa tour of Bangladesh at Chittagong, Jul 21\u201325 2015 \u2013 Match Report|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and 88.1 overs<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/11365/report/817215/day/4|title=2nd Test, South Africa tour of Bangladesh at Dhaka, Jul 30 \u2013 Aug 3 2015 \u2013 Match Report|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> respectively).\n\nStrong performances shown by Bangladesh in ODIs since the ICC Cricket World Cup 2015, winning ODI series against Pakistan, India and South Africa, helped it jump from ninth to seventh in the ODI Team Rankings. Since they were ranked No. 7 in ODIs on 30 September 2015 which was the cut-off date, they have qualified for the [[2017 ICC Champions Trophy]] replacing West Indies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/181968|title=Teams confirmed for ICC Champions Trophy 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, The [[Zimbabwean cricket team in Bangladesh in 2015\u201316|Zimbabwean cricket team]] toured in Bangladesh. The tour consisted of three [[One Day International]]s (ODIs), two [[Twenty20 International]]s (T20Is). Bangladesh won the ODI series 3\u20130 and shared the T20I series 1\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-zimbabwe-2015-16/content/series/931380.html|title=Zimbabwe tour of Bangladesh|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nZimbabwe toured Bangladesh for another T20I series consisting of 4 games in January 2016. Again the series was shared 2\u20132.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-zimbabwe-jan-2015-16/content/series/958411.html|title=Zimbabwe tour of Bangladesh [Jan 2016]|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nThe golden run continued to Bangladesh when they became runner up of [[2016 Asia Cup]], played on home soil.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/asia-cup-2015-16/content/series/966595.html|title=Asia Cup|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> They lost the first match at group stage to India. Then they won against UAE, Sri Lanka (reigning World T20 champions and Asian champions) and Pakistan consecutively to reach the Asia Cup final for the second time. However they were again comprehensively beaten by India in the final.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/966595/scorecard/966765/Bangladesh-vs-India-Final-Asia-Cup|title=Final (N), Asia Cup at Dhaka, Mar 6 2016 \u2013 Match Summary|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nHowever Bangladesh did not have a significant success during the [[2016 ICC World Twenty20]] held in India in March\u2013April 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2016/content/series/901359.html|title=World T20|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Wins against two associates (Netherlands and Oman) and the washed out game against another associate (Ireland) at the group stage saw them reach the Super 10. They returned home losing all four games at the Super 10 stage against full members Pakistan, Australia, India and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2016/engine/series/901359.html?view=pointstable|title=Points Table \u2013 World T20 \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh emerged victorious in another home ODI series (2\u20131) against Afghanistan in Sep\u2013Oct 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/_/id/10798/afg-tour-of-bdesh-2016-17|title=Afghanistan tour of Bangladesh 2016/17 Scores, Fixtures, Tables & News|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nThis was followed by the England tour of Bangladesh,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/_/id/10713/england-tour-of-bdesh-2016-17|title=England tour of Bangladesh 2016/17 Scores, Fixtures, Tables & News|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> where Bangladesh lost the [[English cricket team in Bangladesh in 2016\u201317|ODI]] leg by 2\u20131. But they secured a historic Test win (by 108-runs) against England,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-england-2016-17/content/story/1064022.html | title=Cook rues lack of 'world-class' spin as Bangladesh seal historic win | work=ESPNcricinfo | accessdate=30 October 2016| date=30 October 2016 }}</ref> their first win in 10 attempts, and sharing the two-match test series 1\u20131, after losing the first test narrowly by 22-runs.\n{{Test match\n| date = 28\u201330 October 2016\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|BAN}}\n| team2 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n\n| score-team1-inns1 = 220 (63.5 Overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Tamim Iqbal]] 104 (147)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Moeen Ali]] 5/57 (19.5 Overs)\n\n| score-team2-inns1 = 244 (81.3 Overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Joe Root]] 56 (122)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Mehidy Hasan Miraz]] 6/82 (28 Overs)\n\n| score-team1-inns2 = 296 (66.5 Overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Imrul Kayes]] 78 (120)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Adil Rashid]] 4/52 (11.5 Overs)\n\n| score-team2-inns2 = 164 (45.3 Overs)\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[Alastair Cook]] 59 (117)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = [[Mehidy Hasan Miraz]] 6/77 (21.3 Overs)\n\n| result = Bangladesh won by 108 runs\n| report =<ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/10713/scorecard/1029827/Bangladesh-vs-England-2nd-Test/</ref>\n| venue = [[Shere Bangla National Stadium]], [[Mirpur Model Thana|Mirpur]], [[Dhaka]]\n| umpires = [[Kumar Dharmasena]] (SL) and [[Sundaram Ravi]] (Ind)\n| motm = [[Mehidy Hasan Miraz]]\n| toss = Bangladesh won the toss and elected to bat\n| rain = \n| notes = First Test match win for Bangladesh against England.\n}}\n\nBangladesh [[Bangladesh cricket team in New Zealand in 2016-17|toured New Zealand]] for a complete series in December 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/_/id/10680/bangladesh-tour-of-new-zealand|title=Bangladesh tour of New Zealand 2016/17 Scores, Fixtures, Tables & News|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Bangladesh started the tour with a 3\u20130 whitewash defeat in ODI series and the dawn of new year 2017 saw a similar 3\u20130 whitewash defeat in T20I series. With that, Bangladesh is yet to win a T20I against New Zealand. Further, Bangladesh lost the Test series 2\u20130. However they broke the 123 years old record for the Highest first innings total in tests to lose during the 1st Test vs New Zealand by scoring 595/8 dec.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/new-zealand-v-bangladesh-2016-17/content/story/1077894.html|title=Bangladesh's 595: the highest total in a losing cause|work=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=23 January 2017}}</ref> They finished the tour losing all the games 8\u20130.\n\nThen Bangladesh toured India in February 2017 for the historical first Test match between two countries on Indian soil. India won the game comprehensively by 208 runs, having declared in both innings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/10768/scorecard/1041761/India-vs-Bangladesh-Only-Test-bangladesh-tour-of-india-2016-17/|title=Only Test, Bangladesh tour of India at Hyderabad, Feb 9\u201313 2017 \u2013 Match Summary|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nThe next assignment for Bangladesh was another full away tour in Sri Lanka in March\u2013April 2017. Bangladesh were comprehensively beaten by 259 runs in the first Test. However they were able draw the Test series 1\u20131, by winning the second test by four-wicket. That meant Bangladesh won their 100th Test match becoming one of the four teams to achieve that feat. Further this was Bangladesh's first test match victory against Sri Lanka.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/18949394/sixteen-years-18-tries-one-win|title=Sixteen years, 18 tries, one win|date=19 March 2017}}</ref> \n{{Test match\n| date = 15\u201319 March 2017\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|SRI}}\n| team2 = {{cr-rt|BAN}}\n\n| score-team1-inns1 = 338 (113.3 Overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Dinesh Chandimal]] 138 (300)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Mehidy Hasan Miraz]] 3/90 (21 Overs)\n\n| score-team2-inns1 = 467 (134.1 Overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Shakib Al Hasan]] 116 (159)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Rangana Herath]] 4/82 (34.1 Overs)\n\n| score-team1-inns2 = 319 (113.2 Overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Dimuth Karunaratne]] 126 (244)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Shakib Al Hasan]] 4/74 (36.2 Overs)\n\n| score-team2-inns2 = 191/6 (57.5 Overs)\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[Tamim Iqbal]] 82 (125)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = [[Dilruwan Perera]] 3/59 (22 Overs)\n\n| result = Bangladesh won by 4 wickets\n| report =<ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/11018/scorecard/1083445/Sri-Lanka-vs-Bangladesh-2nd-Test-sl-v-bdesh-2016-17/</ref>\n| venue = [[P Sara Oval]], [[Colombo]]\n| umpires = [[Aleem Dar]] (Pak) and [[Sundaram Ravi]] (Ind)\n| motm = [[Tamim Iqbal]]\n| toss = Sri Lanka won the toss and elected to bat\n| rain = \n| notes = First Test match win for Bangladesh against Sri Lanka. This was the 100th Test match for Bangladesh.\n}}\nBangladesh led the ODI series after two games 1\u20130, since winning the first ODI by 90 runs and the second ODI being washed away by rain. However Sri Lanka won the third ODI by 70 runs, levelling the ODI series 1\u20131. The T20I series was also shared 1\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/_/id/11018/sl-v-bdesh-2016-17|title=Bangladesh tour of Sri Lanka 2016/17 Scores, Fixtures, Tables & News|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Bangladesh finished second at the Ireland Tri-Nation ODI Series held in Ireland, winning 2 (vs New Zealand and Ireland), losing 1 (vs New Zealand) and 1 washed out (vs Ireland) games.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/table/series/11122/ireland-tri-series|title=Ireland Tri-Nation Series Table \u2013 2017|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh started the [[2017 ICC Champions Trophy]] campaign with a defeat in the series opener against England. However a washout against Australia and a famous win against  New Zealand in Cardiff helped them to reach the semi-finals for the first time in Bangladesh cricket history.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/table/series/8037/season/2017/icc-champions-trophy|title=ICC Champions Trophy (ICC KnockOut) Table \u2013 2017|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Finally they were knocked out of the tournament after a huge loss to India by 9 wickets in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8037/scorecard/1022373/Bangladesh-vs-India-2nd-Semi-final-icc-champions-trophy/|title=2nd Semi-final, ICC Champions Trophy at Birmingham, Jun 15 2017 \u2013 Match Summary|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nAustralia toured Bangladesh in August\u2013September 2017 for a two match Test series. Host Bangladesh registered their first test match win ever over Australia when they defeated the touring team by 20 runs during the first Test.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/11143/scorecard/1104284/Bangladesh-vs-Australia-1st-Test-bdesh-v-aus-2017/|title=1st Test, Australia tour of Bangladesh at Dhaka, Aug 27\u201330 2017 \u2013 Match Summary|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> \n{{Test match\n| date = 27\u201330 August 2017\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|BAN}}\n| team2 = {{cr-rt|AUS}}\n\n| score-team1-inns1 = 260 (78.5 Overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Shakib Al Hasan]] 84 (133)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Ashton Agar]] 3/46 (12.5 Overs)\n\n| score-team2-inns1 = 217 (74.5 Overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Matthew Renshaw]] 45 (94)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Shakib Al Hasan]] 5/68 (25.5 Overs)\n\n| score-team1-inns2 = 221 (79.3 Overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Tamim Iqbal]] 78 (155)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Nathan Lyon]] 6/82 (34.3 Overs)\n\n| score-team2-inns2 = 244 (70.5 Overs)\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[David Warner (cricketer)|David Warner]] 112 (135)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = [[Shakib Al Hasan]] 5/85 (28 Overs)\n\n| result = Bangladesh won by 20 runs\n| report =<ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/11143/scorecard/1104284/Bangladesh-vs-Australia-1st-Test-bdesh-v-aus-2017/</ref>\n| venue = [[Shere Bangla National Stadium]], [[Mirpur Model Thana|Mirpur]], [[Dhaka]]\n| umpires = [[Aleem Dar]] (Pak) and [[Nigel Long]] (Eng)\n| motm = [[Shakib Al Hasan]]\n| toss = Bangladesh won the toss and elected to bat\n| rain = \n| notes = First Test match win for Bangladesh against Australia. \n}}\nHowever Bangladesh was unable to secure the series victory, since Australia won the second Test by 7 wickets and the series was shared 1\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/_/id/11143/bdesh-v-aus-2017|title=Australia tour of Bangladesh 2017 Scores, Fixtures, Tables & News|work=ESPNcricinfo|date=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September\u2013October 2017 Bangladesh toured South Africa to play 2 Tests, 3 ODIs and 2 T20Is where Bangladesh was whitewashed 0\u20137 across formats.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/_/id/10904/bangladesh-tour-of-sa-2017-18|title=Bangladesh tour of South Africa 2017/18 Scores, Fixtures, Tables & News|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Team South Africa was too strong for Bangladesh and these games were extremely one-sided, creating several new team and personal records. Bangladesh lost two test by 333 runs and by an innings and 254 runs respectively. The latter being the biggest Test win ever for South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/20954476/bangladesh-demolished-rabada-rise|title=Rabada on the rise|date=8 October 2017}}</ref> South Africa won the 1st ODI by 10 wickets which registered the highest target (279) chased down without losing a wicket in ODIs. In last two ODIs Bangladesh lost comprehensively by 104 and by 200 runs. Later Bangladesh also lost the 2 T20Is by 20 runs and 83 runs. During the 2nd T20I David Miller scored the fastest T20I century ever recorded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/21210612/david-miller-smashes-record-fastest-t20i-ton|title=Miller smashes record for fastest T20I ton|date=29 October 2017}}</ref> However, during the middle of this tour Bangladesh was qualified for the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]] since they were at No. 7 of ICC ODI rankings by 30 September 2017 cut-off date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/476792|title=Sri Lanka qualify for ICC Cricket World Cup 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 November 2017, BCB president Nazmul Hassan announced that Hathurusingha submitted resignation from the post of Bangladesh head coach during the team's tour of South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/21351286/hathurusingha-submitted-resignation-sa-tour-bcb-president|title=Hathurusingha submitted resignation during SA tour \u2013 BCB president|date=9 November 2017}}</ref> During his tenure, Bangladesh won 6 Tests (in 21), 25 ODIs (in 52) and 10 T20Is (in 29) which is arguably the most successful era of Bangladesh Cricket.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=1;filter=advanced;orderby=start;spanmax2=09+Nov+2017;spanmin1=10+Jun+2014;spanval1=span;spanval2=span;team=25;template=results;type=team |title= Bangladesh in 2017}}</ref> Further, under his wings Bangladesh reached quarter finals of [[2015 Cricket World Cup]], qualified and later reached semi-finals of [[2017 ICC Champions Trophy]], qualified for [[2019 Cricket World Cup]], became runner up of [[2016 Asia Cup]], defeated India, Pakistan and South Africa in home bilateral series, climbed up to No. 6 of ODI rankings, registered their first Test wins against England, Sri Lanka and Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/1125712.html|title=Uncertainty over Hathurusingha's future as Bangladesh coach|date=9 November 2017}}</ref> He was instrumental in Bangladesh beginning to actively picking more pace bowlers in their attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/19625529/how-bangladesh-came-pace-heavy-odi-attack|title=How Bangladesh came to have a pace-heavy ODI attack|date=14 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nShakib Al Hasan has replaced Mushfiqur Rahim as Bangladesh's Test captain, starting with the upcoming Sri Lanka tour in January 2018. Mahmudullah will take over the vice-captaincy from Tamim Iqbal while the BCB is yet to announce a new coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/21725908/shakib-al-hasan-named-new-bangladesh-test-captain|title=Shakib named new Bangladesh Test captain|date=10 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Under Richard Halsall (2018) ===\nBCB chairman announced that their assistant coach [[Richard Halsall]], will be in charge of coaching the side ahead of the Tri-nation ODI series held in January 2018 at home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/21931420/bangladesh-head-coach-zimbabwe-sri-lanka-tri-series|title=Bangladesh without head coach for Zimbabwe, Sri Lanka tri-series|date=January 2018}}</ref> Convincing wins against low ranked opponents, Sri Lanka and Zimbabwe, in the first three group games saw Bangladesh reach the finals. Bangladesh recorded their biggest win in ODI cricket (won by 163 runs) against Sri Lanka during the process. However Bangladesh were bowled out for 82 (which was their ninth-lowest ODI total) and lost by 10 wickets in the last group game against Sri Lanka. They met Sri Lanka in the finals and lost the match by 79 runs, extending their win-less run in tournament finals. The 1st Test against Sri Lanka was a high scoring draw. Later, Bangladesh lost the 2nd Test by 215 runs inside 3 days, conceding the Test series 1\u20130. Bangladesh also lost the T20I series 3\u20130.\n\n=== Under Courtney Walsh (2018) ===\n[[File:Bangladesh team on practice session at Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium (4).jpg|thumb|250px|Bangladesh team on practice session at Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium]]\nCourtney Walsh acted as the interim coach for [[2018 Nidahas Trophy]], a triangular T20I series held in Sri Lanka in March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22584350/courtney-walsh-named-bangladesh-interim-head-coach|title=Walsh named Bangladesh's interim head coach|date=26 February 2018}}</ref> Bangladesh lost the tournament final against India, after reaching there defeating Sri Lanka twice in group matches.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/_/id/18547/season/2018/nidahas-twenty20-tri-series|title=Nidahas Twenty20 Tri-Series 2018 Scores, Fixtures, Tables & News|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 May, Bangladesh broke into the top eight of the Test rankings for the first time, as a result of the ICC's annual update to the rankings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/23373180/india-widen-gap-top-test-rankings|title=India widen gap at the top of Test rankings|date=May 2018}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh got whitewashed in a 3 match T20I series [[Bangladeshi cricket team against Afghanistan in India in 2018|against Afghanistan in India]], losing their matches by 45 runs, by 6 wickets and by 1 run respectively. This recorded Bangladesh's first T20I match loss ever and their first T20I series loss against Afghans as well.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/1148392.html |title=Advantage Afghanistan in spin-friendly Dehradun |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Under Steve Rhodes (2018\u20132019)===\nBCB appointed former England wicketkeeper [[Steve Rhodes]] the Bangladesh head coach for all three formats in early March ahead of West Indies tour.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/23701081/steve-rhodes-set-become-next-bangladesh-coach|work=ESPNcricinfo|title=Steve Rhodes set to become next Bangladesh coach|date=5 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh hit an all-time low when they were dismissed for 43 (their lowest score in Tests) during the 1st Test against West Indies at North Sound and eventually lost the test by an innings and 219 runs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/23998251/stats-all-low-bangladesh|title=Lowest toal by Bangladesh in test|work=ESPNcricinfo|date=4 July 2018}}</ref> Later Bangladesh lost the 2nd Test by 166 runs and lost the series 2\u20130. Later they performed well in limited overs formats and eventually ended up the tour by winning the three match ODI and T20I series by 2\u20131 margin each.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/103487/liton-das-mustafizur-rahman-help-bangladesh-to-series-win|work=Cricbuzz|title=Bangaldesh won first T20I series outside Asia since 2012}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh started their [[Asia Cup 2018]] campaign with a win over Sri Lanka by 137 runs, which was their biggest win, by runs in ODIs away from home. Even-though they faced a heavy loss in their next match at group stage against Afghanistan, (lost by 136 runs \u2013 Bangladesh's biggest lost, by runs in ODIs against Afghanistan), they have progressed to the Super Four stage. Bangladesh lost to India by 7 wickets, narrowly won against Afghanistan by 3 runs and defeated Pakistan by 37 runs at the Super Four stage to reach the [[2018 Asia Cup Final|Final of the Asia Cup]]. At the Final, they have lost to India by 3 wickets, extending their win-less record in tournament Finals.\n\nIn October\u2013November, Bangladesh hosted a three match ODI and two match test series [[Zimbabwean cricket team in Bangladesh in 2018\u201319|against Zimbabwe]]. Bangladesh won the ODI series 3\u20130 while they drew the test series 1\u20131, losing the first test of the series at [[Sylhet International Cricket Stadium|Sylhet]] which was the inaugural test of the venue.\n\n[[West Indian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2018\u201319|West Indies toured Bangladesh]] for a full series in November\u2013December. Bangladesh won the 2 match test series 2\u20130. By defeating West Indies in the 2nd test by an innings and 184 runs, Bangladesh recorded their first innings victory in Test cricket. Bangladesh also won the 3 match ODI series by 2\u20131 margin. But lost the T20I series by 2\u20131 margin.\n\n{{Two-innings cricket match\n| date = 30 November\u20134 December 2018\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|BAN}}\n| team2 = {{cr|WIN}}\n\n| score-team1-inns1 = 508 (154 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Mahmudullah]] 136 (242)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Kraigg Brathwaite]] 2/57 (15 overs)\n\n| score-team2-inns1 = 111 (36.4 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Shimron Hetmyer]] 39 (53)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Mehedi Hasan]] 7/58 (16 overs)\n\n| score-team1-inns2 = \n| runs-team1-inns2 = \n| wickets-team1-inns2 =\n\n| score-team2-inns2 = 213 (59.2 overs) ([[follow-on|f/o]])\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[Shimron Hetmyer]] 93 (92)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = [[Mehedi Hasan]] 5/59 (20 overs)\n\n| result = Bangladesh won by an innings and 184 runs\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1153312.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium]], [[Dhaka]]\n| umpires = [[Aleem Dar]] (Pak) and [[Ruchira Palliyaguruge]] (SL)\n| motm = [[Mehedi Hasan]] (Ban)\n| toss = Bangladesh won the toss and elected to bat.\n| rain = \n| notes = Bangladesh enforced the [[follow-on]] for the first time in Tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.supersport.com/cricket/bangladesh-v-windies-201819/news/181202_Bangladesh_rout_Windies_for_111_enforce_followon |title=Bangladesh rout Windies for 111, enforce follow-on |work=SuperSport |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref>\n*''[[Mehedi Hasan]] took the [[List of Bangladesh Test cricket records#Best Bowling Figure in a Match|best match figures by a Bangladesh bowler]] in Tests (12/117).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/sport/cricket/mehidy-hasan-tears-through-west-indies-as-bangladesh-wrap-up-test-series-in-style-1.798204 |title=Mehidy Hasan tears through West Indies as Bangladesh wrap up Test series in style |work=The National |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref>\n*''This was Bangladesh's [[List of Bangladesh Test cricket records#Largest victory (by runs)|biggest winning margin by runs]], and their first win by an innings in Tests.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/18783/report/1153312/day/3/bangladesh-vs-west-indies-2nd-test-wi-in-bangladesh-2018-19 |title=Mehidy 12-for scripts record Bangladesh win |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\nBangladesh toured New Zealand in February\u2013March 2019. Bangladesh got whitewashed in the 3 match ODI series. Bangladesh lost the first Test at Hamilton by an innings and 52 runs. Later they have lost the second Test at Wellington by an innings and 12 runs even after the first two days play were abandoned due to rain. The third test was canceled following the [[Christchurch mosque shootings]], which the team narrowly escaped.<ref>[https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/cricket/111314794/bangladesh-cricket-team-escape-christchurch-mosque-shooting Christchurch mosque shootings: Black Caps v Bangladesh test cancelled], Stuff, 15 March 2019</ref>\n\n{{Single-innings cricket match|bg=#eee\n| date = 17 May 2019\n| time = 10:45\n| daynight = \n| team1 = {{cr-rt|WIN}}\n| team2 = {{cr|BAN}}\n| score1 = 152/1 (24 overs)\n| runs1 = [[Shai Hope]] 74 (64)\n| wickets1 = [[Mehedi Hasan]] 1/22 (4 overs)\n| score2 = 213/5 (22.5 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Soumya Sarkar]] 66 (41)\n| wickets2 = [[Raymon Reifer]] 2/23 (3.5 overs)\n| result = Bangladesh won by 5 wickets ([[Duckworth\u2013Lewis\u2013Stern method|DLS method]])\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1168514.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Malahide Cricket Club Ground|The Village]], [[Malahide]]\n| umpires = [[Richard Kettleborough]] (Eng) and [[Paul Reynolds (umpire)|Paul Reynolds]] (Ire)\n| motm = [[Mosaddek Hossain]] (Ban)\n| toss = Bangladesh won the toss and elected to field.\n| rain = Bangladesh were set a revised target of 210 runs from 24 overs due to rain.\n| notes = \n}}\nBangladesh won their first ever multi-team ODI tournament final at Dublin on 17 May 2019 defeating West Indies by 5 wickets (D/L method) at the [[2019 Ireland Tri-Nation Series]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/11122/scorecard/1168514/bangladesh-vs-west-indies-final-ireland-tri-nation-series-2019|title=Full Scorecard of Bangladesh vs West Indies, Ireland Tri-Nation Series, Final \u2013 Score Report {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket/story/ireland-tr-series-final-bangladesh-vs-west-indies-odi-mosaddek-hossain-1527952-2019-05-18 |title=Bangladesh beat West Indies to lift maiden multi-nation ODI trophy|work=India Today|date=17 May 2019}}</ref> Bangladesh reached the finals defeating West Indies twice and Ireland once during league phase and the other league match against Ireland was washed out due to rain.\n\nEven though they entered the tournament with high expectations, Bangladesh finished 8th at the group stage of [[2019 Cricket World Cup]] and were unable to reach the semi-finals, after winning only three of their nine matches. In July 2019, Rhodes' contract with the BCB was terminated, following the team's eighth-place finish in the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27147893/bangladesh-part-ways-coach-steve-rhodes |title=Bangladesh part ways with coach Steve Rhodes |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Under Khaled Mahmud (2019)===\n[[Khaled Mahmud]], who played for Bangladesh in the [[1999 Cricket World Cup]], was subsequently appointed as interim coach after [[Steve Rhodes]]'s contract being terminated. His first assignment in charge was Bangladesh's [[Bangladeshi cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2019|three-match ODI tour of Sri Lanka]], from 26 to 31 July 2019, which Bangladesh received a whitewash losing the series 0\u20133.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1298150|title=Sri Lanka seal ODI clean sweep of Bangladesh|work=icc-cricket.com|date=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Under Russell Domingo (2019\u2013present)===\n[[File:Day night test at Eden gardens.jpeg|thumb|Bangladesh played their first ever Day/night test match against India at [[Eden Gardens]] in November 2019]] \nBCB appointed [[Russell Domingo]] as the head coach for the national team for a 2-year contract on 17 August 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/109404/russell-domingo-appointed-bangladesh-head-coach|title=Russell Domingo appointed Bangladesh head coach|work=Cricbuzz|date=17 August 2019}}</ref>\nIn his first assignment as coach [[Afghan cricket team in Bangladesh in 2019\u201320|Bangladesh lost to Afghanistan]] in one-off Test match at [[Zohur Ahmed Chowdhury Stadium|Chittagong]] in September 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27579973/afghanistan-show-test-win-result-long-term-planning-mental-toughness |title=Afghanistan show Test win result of long-term planning and mental toughness |work=Cricinfo|publisher=ESPN|date=10 September 2019}}</ref> But in [[2019\u201320 Bangladesh Tri-Nation Series|the tri-series]], comprising [[Afghanistan national cricket team|Afghanistan]] and [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]], Bangladesh reached to final winning 3 of their 4 group matches. But the final match with Afghanistan was washed away.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/series/19449/report/1197146/bangladesh-vs-afghanistan-final-bangladesh-twenty20-tri-series |title=Trophy shared as rain washes out final in Dhaka |work=Cricinfo|publisher=ESPN|date=10 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Bangladeshi cricket team in India in 2019\u201320|Bangladesh then toured India in October\u2013November]] to play 3 T20Is and 2 test matches. Bangladesh started their [[World Test Championship]] campaign with this test series. Just before few days of the tour Bangladesh's regular Test and T20I captain [[Shakib Al Hasan]] was banned for 2 years by ICC for breaching ''ICC Code of Conduct''. Subsequently, [[Mominul Haque]] was given the charge of test captaincy and [[Mahmudullah]] as T20I captain. Bangladesh won the first match of the tour, first T20I at [[Arun Jaitley Stadium|Delhi]] by 7 wickets and lost the remaining 2 matches by 8 wickets and 30 runs respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/sports/cricket/india-vs-bangladesh-3rd-t20i-win-series-report-6113339/ |title=Deepak Chahar demolishes Bangladesh with 6/7, India win T20I series 2\u20131 |work=Indian Expresss |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref>\nBangladesh lost both the test matches by innings margin as their batsmen failed to capitalize. Wheres the second test was first ever [[Day/night cricket|Day/night test match]] played by both teams.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1498140 |title=Bangladesh brace for another historic first against India |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, when [[Zimbabwean cricket team in Bangladesh in 2019\u201320|Zimbabwe toured Bangladesh]], the home team won the one-off test match by an innings and 106 runs, which is Bangladesh's first test win since Domingo took charge as the head coach of the team as well as it was their only second test match win by innings margin.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bangladesh beat Zimbabwe by innings and 106 runs |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/sports/bangladesh-cricket/news/mominul-mushy-look-secure-dominant-position-1872286 |accessdate=25 February 2020 |work=The Daily Star |date=24 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Bangladesh won the ODI series 3\u20130, with Mortaza recording his 50th win in an ODI match as captain with victory in the third match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cricketworld.com/3rd-odi-bangladesh-v-zimbabwe-bangladesh-win-by-123-runs-dls-/62345.htm |title=3rd ODI Bangladesh v Zimbabwe: Bangladesh win by 123 runs (DLS) |work=Cricket World |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Governing body==\n{{main|Bangladesh Cricket Board}}\nThe Bangladesh Cricket Board (BCB) is the governing body for the Bangladeshi cricket team<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.bdcricteam.com/ |title=Bangladesh Cricket Team |publisher=Bangladesh Cricket}}</ref> and the sport in the country. The BCB is responsible for maintaining grounds and promoting the sport. It was founded in 1972 as the Bangladesh Cricket Control Board.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.bcb.com.bd/about-bcb.html |title=About BCB |publisher=Bangladesh Cricket Board |accessdate=11 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110311101206/http://bcb.com.bd/about-bcb.html |archive-date=11 March 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Its first constitution was drafted in 1976.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/paper-edition/others/panorama/18958-bangladesh-cricket-at-the-crossroad.html |title=Bangladesh cricket at the crossroad |work=[[The Independent (Bangladesh)|The Independent]] |date=12 November 2010 |accessdate=11 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717003614/http://www.theindependentbd.com/paper-edition/others/panorama/18958-bangladesh-cricket-at-the-crossroad.html |archivedate=17 July 2011  }}</ref> The board changed its name, dropping \"control\" from its title, in January 2007.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/276356.html |title=Board's name amended by government notification |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=13 January 2007 |accessdate=11 March 2011}}</ref> The president of the BCB is appointed by the government of Bangladesh.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/story/521351.html |title=ICC gives boards two years to fall in line |first=Osman |last=Samiuddin |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=30 June 2011 |accessdate=8 July 2011}}</ref> The board also controls the team's sponsorship. Since 2003 telecommunications company [[Grameenphone]] has sponsored the men and women's national teams. Between 2007 and 2011 they invested {{BDTConvert|151.5|m|lk=yes}} in developing sport in the country.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.grameenphone.com/about-us/media-center/press-release/2009/148/gp-official-sponsor-bangladesh-national-men%E2%80%99s-women%E2%80%99s-cricket-teams |title=GP Official Sponsors of Bangladesh National Men's & Women's Cricket Teams |publisher=Grameenphone |date=17 December 2009 |accessdate=22 August 2011}}</ref> In 2006 the Board established an academy to encourage the development of young and inexperienced players.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/243222.html |title=Bangladesh to set up academy |date=4 April 2006 |accessdate=22 September 2011}}</ref> The Board issues central contracts to the national players and issuing match fees. In 2005 players were given about $1,000 for each Test they played and $500 per ODI.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/222634.html |title=BCB announce 'perform and earn more' payroll |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 October 2005 |accessdate=22 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==International grounds==\n{{Main|List of cricket grounds in Bangladesh}}\n{{see also|List of international cricket five-wicket hauls in Bangladesh cricket grounds}}\n{{see also|List of international cricket centuries at the Sher-e-Bangla Cricket Stadium}}\n\n===International contribution by Bangladesh grounds===\n''Listed in order of match first used for international match''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"  \n|-\n! Venue !! City !! Capacity !! First Used !!Tests !!ODIs !!T20Is\n|-\n! colspan=7|Active Venues\n|-\n|[[Khan Shaheb Osman Ali Stadium]] ||