heed Chandu]]</small>|position=left|lat =24.839617|long=89.365225}} \n{{location map~|Bangladesh|label=<small>[[Sheikh Abu Naser Stadium|Sheikh Abu Naser]]</small>|position=right|lat=22.844475|long=89.537353}} \n{{location map~|Bangladesh|label=<small>[[Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium|Sher-e-Bangla]]</small>|position=top|lat=23.806917|long=90.363583}} \n{{location map~|Bangladesh|label=<small>[[Sylhet International Cricket Stadium|SIC]]</small>|position=left|lat=24.920781|long=91.868653}} \n{{location map~|Bangladesh|label=<small>[[Zohur Ahmed Chowdhury Stadium|ZAC]]</small>|position=left|lat=22.355803|long=91.767919}} \n}}\n\n==Fan following==\n[[File:Bangladesh Players Celebrate Fall of Wicket.jpg|thumb|left|300px|Bangladesh playing against Zimbabwe in 2009. Fans can be seen in the background waving a Bangladesh flag.]]\n \nBefore Bangladesh had even secured Test status, cricket fans in the country took the game seriously; when the team lost an ODI against Kenya in March 1999, several hundred fans protested outside the offices of the [[Bangladesh Cricket Board]] (BCB).<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/151605.html |title=Meril International Tournament 1998\u201399, fifth match: Bangladesh v Kenya |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=10 March 2011}}</ref> On learning of Bangladesh's promotion to Test status, thousands of people celebrated on the streets. Then Prime Minister [[Sheikh Hasin/ref> However, during the middle of this tour Bangladesh was qualified for the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]] since they were at No. 7 of ICC ODI rankings by 30 September 2017 cut-off date.ref>{{cite news|url= http://stats.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/engine/records/team/match_results.html?class=2;id=476;type=ground|title= M. A. Aziz Stadium ODI matches|work= ESPNcricinfo|accessdate= 20 November 2012}}a]] remarked that \"I can't express my joy in words at this happiest hour of the nation\".<ref name=\"happiest hour\">{{citation |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/807107.stm |title=Bangladesh delight at Test status |work=BBC News|date=26 June 2000 |accessdate=21 April 2011}}</ref> At the time cricket was the second-most popular sport in the country behind football.<ref name=\"happiest hour\"/> When Bangladesh began its first Test match on 10 November 2000 at [[Bangabandhu National Stadium]] in Dhaka, the stadium was nearly full on the first day as around 40,000&nbsp;people watched the team take on India. As the match partly overlapped with the festival of [[Shab-e-Barat]], numbers attending declined as the match progressed.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/154207.html |first=Richard |last=Hobson |title=The Indians in Bangladesh, 2000\u201301 |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=10 March 2011}}</ref> [[File:Supporters of the Bangladesh cricket team.jpg|thumb|Supporters of the Bangladesh cricket team]] In 2011, Bangladeshi politician [[Saber Hossain Chowdhury]] opined that \"In Bangladesh cricket is not simply a game, it is a symbol of national unity\",<ref name=\"fan following\">{{citation |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/other_international/bangladesh/9420128.stm |title=Cricket World Cup: Nation unites behind Bangladesh |first=Akbar |last=Hossain |publisher=BBC Sport |date=9 March 2011 |accessdate=10 March 2011}}</ref> and in the words of AHM Mostofa Kamal, president of the BCB in 2011, \"People of [[Bangladesh]] take cricket religiously\".<ref name=\"fan following\"/>\n \nThe people of Bangladesh are referred as \"the most passionate cricket fans\" among the cricket world. When Bangladesh are victorious, the fans sometimes take to the streets in celebration. When Bangladesh defeated India in the 2007 World Cup, thousands of people celebrated into the night on the streets of Dhaka despite there being a ban on public gatherings at the time.<ref>{{citation |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/6536593.stm |title=Cricket win prompts Dhaka parties |work=BBC News|date=8 April 2007 |accessdate=10 March 2011}}</ref> Although fans are jubilant in victory, they can also be vocal in defeat. When Bangladesh lost to England in an ODI in November 2003, the then captain Khaled Mahmud was booed off the field.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/155899.html |title=First One-Day International: Bangladesh v England, 2003\u201304 |publisher=Wisden Cricketers' Almanac |accessdate=10 March 2011}}</ref> During the 2011 World Cup, Bangladesh succumbed to a record defeat against West Indies, registering the team's lowest score in ODIs. The buses of both teams were stoned (Bangladesh's intentionally, West Indies' mistakenly), as was Shakib Al Hasan's house.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/504317.html |title=Bangladesh bus was also hit, says Ian Pont |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=4 March 2011 |accessdate=10 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Team colours==\nIn Test cricket, Bangladesh wears [[cricket whites]], with the BCB logo on the left chest and the sponsor's logo on the right chest. Fielders wear a dark green cap or a white wide brim sunhat. The helmets are also dark green. In limited overs cricket, Bangladesh wears a green uniform with red being the secondary colour and the BCB logo on chest and the sponsor's logo on the centre and \"BANGLADESH\" written underneath in red letters, with the fielders wearing a green baseball cap with red accents or a green wide-brimmed hat. During [[International Cricket Council|ICC]] tournaments, the sponsor's logo is placed on the left sleeve.  In the [[1999 Cricket World Cup]], Bangladesh wore an olive green uniform with yellow accents and an horizontal stripe with tiger-stripe motif on the chest.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/181003|title=Classic World Cup Kits \u2013 1999|access-date=11 September 2018}}</ref> On 6 September 2018 [[Unilever Bangladesh Limited|Uniliver Bangladesh]] became the team sponsor for the period of 2018 to 2020.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.tigercricket.com.bd/2018/09/06/media-release-unilever-bangladesh-limited-becomes-national-team-sponsors/|title=Unilever Bangladesh Limited becomes National Team Sponsors|work=Tigercricket.com.bd|date=6 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+  \n! Period/tournament !! Kit manufacturer !! Sponsor\n|-\n| 1971\u20131999 || colspan=\"2\" {{n/a}}\n|-\n| [[1999 Cricket World Cup]] || [[Asics]] || [[Veetee Rice|Veetee]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/82441.html|title=Bowled over by Veetee? (19 May 1999)|work=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=11 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2000\u20132004 || rowspan=2| [[AJ Sports]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/112196.html|title=BCCSL appoints AJ Sports as official clothing sponsor|work=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=11 September 2018}}</ref> ||  [[Beximco]]\n|-\n| [[2003 Cricket World Cup]] || [[Mobil 1]]\n|-\n| 2005\u20132008 || Ihsan Sports<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bdnews24.com/sport/2005/07/09/ihsan-sports-to-sponsor-bangladesh-s-five-teams-including-the-national-cricket-team|title=Ihsan Sports to sponsor Bangladesh's five teams including the national cricket team|access-date=11 September 2018}}</ref> || rowspan=2| [[Grameen Phone]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/216280.html|title=Bangladesh strike deal with GrameenPhone|work=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=11 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2009\u20132011|| [[Bata Shoes|Bata]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-82532|title=Bata clothing sponsors for cricket teams|date=3 April 2009|work=The Daily Star|access-date=11 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2012\u20132015 || rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a}} || [[Sahara India Pariwar|Sahara]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/cricket-bangladesh-sponsor/cricket-sahara-group-set-to-beco