132003).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/284049.html |title=Records / One-Day Internationals / Team records / Most consecutive matches without victory |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |accessdate=20 July 2015}}</ref>\n* Only Test side which have lost the first ODI they have played against five non-Test sides (Canada 2003, Kenya 2003, Ireland 2007, Netherlands 2010 and Afghanistan 2014).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/asia-cup-2014/content/story/724301.html |title=Bangladesh's first-encounter |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=March 2014 |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref>\n* The highest innings total in a losing cause 595/8 dec vs New Zealand in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/18485552/highest-total-losing-cause |title = Bangladesh's 595: The highest total in a losing cause|date = 16 January 2017}}</ref>\n* Bangladesh has taken 16 years and 12 days\u2014the least amount of time among all 10 Test-playing countries\u2014to reach the landmark figure of playing 100 tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/cricket/youngest-test-side-bangladesh-cricket-team-set-for-century-milestone/story-Zhq4yrpKYbI8yRJ4RBFI6M.html |title=Youngest Test side Bangladesh cricket team set for century milestone |work=Hindustan Times |date=14 March 2017 |accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n* Only test side which have not been involved in any tied international matches.\n\n===By Bangladeshi players===\n* [[Aminul Islam (cricketer, born 1968)|Aminul Islam]] became the third cricketer to score a century on their country's inaugural test in 2000 against [[Indian national cricket team|India]]. He achieved this feat after [[Charles Bannerman]] ([[Australia national cricket team|Australia]]) and [[David Houghton (cricketer)|Dave Houghton]] ([[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]]) while [[Ireland cricket team|Irish cricketer]] [[Kevin O'Brien (cricketer)|Kevin O'Brien]] was the latest and the fourth member to join this elite club.<ref name=\"BAN18yrsRecord\">{{citation |url=https://www.prothomalo.com/sports/article/1564616/%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%82%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%A6%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B6%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%A4-%E0%A6%A4%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%A4%E0%A7%8B-%E0%A6%AE%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%A0%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B6%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AC-%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A1 |title=Some bitter-sweet records of Bangladeh cricket team in test |work=[[Prothom Alo]] |accessdate= 10 November 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Mohammad Ashraful]] holds the record for the youngest cricketer to make a Test century. He was 17 years and 61 days old when he made 114 against [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]] at [[Sinhalese Sports Club Ground|Colombo]] on 8 September 2001, during his Test debut.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/282986.html|title=Records {{!}} Test matches {{!}} Batting records {{!}} Youngest player to score a hundred {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=Cricinfo|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n* In 2005 against [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]], [[Enamul Haque (Sylhet cricketer, born 1986)|Enamul Haque Jr.]] became the youngest bowler ever to take a 10 wicket-haul in test at the age of 18 years 40 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283789.html|title=Records {{!}} Test matches {{!}} Bowling records {{!}} Youngest player to take ten-wickets-in-a-match {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=Cricinfo|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n* [[Mashrafe Mortaza]] was the leading wicket-taker in [[One Day International|ODI]]s in 2006, with 49 wickets in 27 matches.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?class=2;id=2006;type=year |title=Records / 2006 / One-Day Internationals / Most wickets |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref>\n* On 21 November 2012, [[Abul Hasan (cricketer)|Abul Hasan]] became only the second Test cricketer in history to make a century at number 10 on debut, against the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]] at [[Sheikh Abu Naser Stadium|Khulna]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/duff-peer-bangladesh-cricketer-equals-110yearold-test-record-20121121-29rbr.html |title=Duff peer: Bangladesh cricketer equals 110-year-old Test record |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=22 November 2012| accessdate=26 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-west-indies-2012/content/story/592201.html |title = No. 10 Abul Hasan's debut ton revives Bangladesh|date = 21 November 2012}}</ref>\n* On 13 October 2013, against [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]] at [[Zohur Ahmed Chowdhury Stadium|Chittagong]], [[Sohag Gazi]] became the first cricketer ever to score a century and take a hat-trick in the same Test match.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-new-zealand-2013-14/content/story/679189.html |title=Gazi shines as Test ends in draw |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=13 October 2013 |accessdate=13 December 2014}}</ref>\n* In 2014, [[Shakib Al Hasan]] became only third cricketer after [[Ian Botham]] ([[England cricket team|England]]) and [[Imran Khan]] ([[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]]) to score a century and to pick up 10 wickets in same test.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/287370.html|title=Records {{!}} Test matches {{!}} All-round records {{!}} 100 runs and 10 wickets in a match {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=Cricinfo|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n* [[Taijul Islam]] became the first bowler ever to take a hat-trick on debut in an ODI against [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]] at [[Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium|Dhaka]] on 1 December 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-zimbabwe-2014-15/content/story/806027.html |title=Taijul debut hat-trick seals 5\u20130 win |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=1 December 2014 |accessdate=1 December 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Shakib Al Hasan]] became the first player in history to hold the number 1 positions in all three formats of cricket, in the all-rounder category on 12 January 2015.<ref name=\"news.com.au\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.prothom-alo.com/sport/news/57883/Shakib-top-all-rounder-in-all-3-formats |title=Shakib top all-rounder in all 3 formats |work=Prothom Alo |accessdate=9 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310181901/http://en.prothom-alo.com/sport/news/57883/Shakib-top-all-rounder-in-all-3-formats |archive-date=10 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Mustafizur Rahman]] became the first cricketer ever to take 11 wickets in his first two ODIs when he took 5/50 against [[India national cricket team|India]] on 18 June 2015 and then 6/43 against the same team three days later. Both matches were played at Dhaka.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-india-2015/content/story/890051.html |title=Mustafizur's record-breaking ODI genesis |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=21 June 2015 |accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref>\n* Until 25 July 2015, [[Elias Sunny]] was the only player to be nominated as the Man of the match in two formats of the international cricket as a debutant. He made it in Test(v [[West Indies national cricket team|West Indies]] in 2011) & T20I(v [[Ireland national cricket team|Ireland]] in 2012).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/531986.html |title=Test debutant Sunny became Player of the match |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=25 October 2011 |accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/531986.html |title=T20I debutant Sunny became Player of the match |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=18 July 2012 |accessdate=19 July 2012}}</ref> [[Mustafizur Rahman]], being only second to Elias Sunny, did it in ODI(v [[India national cricket team|India]]) and in Test(v [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]]) both in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bangla.bdnews24.com/cricket/article1001610.bdnews |title=\u09ae\u09c1\u09b8\u09cd\u09a4\u09be\u09ab\u09bf\u099c\u09c7\u09b0 \u0985\u09a8\u09a8\u09cd\u09af \u0987\u09a4\u09bf\u09b9\u09be\u09b8 |publisher=[[bdnews24.com]] |date=25 July 2015 |accessdate=26 July 2015}}</ref>\n* On 7 June 2018 in the 3rd T20I against [[Afghan national cricket team|Afghanistan]] by taking the wicket of [[Najibullah Zadran]], [[Shakib Al Hasan]] became the quickest All-rounder to achieve the double of 10,000 runs and 500 wickets in 302 international matches and became only 3rd cricketer to do so following [[Jacques Kallis]] and [[Shahid Afridi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.sportskeeda.com/cricket/stats-shakib-al-hasan-fastest-to-register-10-000-runs-and-500-wickets-in-international-cricket-history|title=Shakib became the quickest All-rounder to achieve the double of 10000 runs & 500 wickets}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cricket|Bangladesh}} \n* [[Bangladesh Premier League]] \n* [[Bangladesh national women's cricket team]] \n* [[List of Bangladesh national cricket captains]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{commons category|Bangladesh national cricket team}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.tigercricket.com.bd}}\n{{Asian Games cricket men's tournament winners}}\n{{Bangladesh national cricket team}} \n{{National sports teams of Bangladesh}} \n{{International cricket tours of Bangladesh}}  \n{{National cricket teams}}\n\n[[Category:Cricket in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:National cricket teams|Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:National sports teams of Bangladesh|Cricket]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh in international cricket]]\n", "name_user": "Vallabharebejnd", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bangladesh_national_cricket_team"}
